{"title_page": "Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture\n| type = [[Private company]]\n| industry = [[Architecture]], [[urban planning]], [[master planning]]\n| founded = 1999\n| founder = Oliver Lang, Cynthia Wilson\n| hq_location = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| num_employees = 6\n| homepage = https://lwpac.net/\n}}\nThe '''Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture''' (LWPAC) is an [[architectural firm]] founded in 1999 by Oliver Lang and Cynthia Wilson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westernliving.ca/architects-of-the-year-lang-wilson|title=Western Living Magazine|last=Mckenzie|first=Kevin Hinton & Ryan|website=Western Living Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> It was first launched in [[New York City]] before being permanently based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], where it evolved into an [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] business.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadian-architects.com/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc|title=LWPAC \u2013 Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture \u2013 Vancouver BC, Canada \u2013 Architects -|website=Canadian-Architects|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Architecture|architectural]] and cultural firm delivers unified resolutions to serve [[Innovation|innovative]] ideas for projects<ref name=\":0\" />. LWPAC works on projects that are large scale; [[urban planning]], and housing complexes, as well as small scale such as [[Installation art|art installations]]<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nLWPAC was co-founded by German-Canadian architect and urban [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]], Oliver Lang, and Canadian designer and cultural entrepreneur, Cindy Wilson.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.westernliving.ca/architects-of-the-year-lang-wilson|title=Practice|last=|first=|date=|website=LWPAC|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> They have worked together in Canada, United States and Germany, to bring-forth a communal and global experience to their projects<ref name=\":1\" />. LWPAC has developed an intent over the years, to serve as a platform for architecture and urban design. Together, this multidisciplinary collaboration forwards [[culture]] as the driving force towards intelligent and [[Innovation|innovative]] designs<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n== Expertise ==\nLWPAC aims to create projects based on their [[Sustainable architecture|sustainable]] outcome through connective, [[Adaptive architecture|adaptable]] and generative ideas<ref name=\":0\" />. They take on a sustainable approach by analyzing urban contexts to ensure passive strategies can be applied to meet low energy demands. A minimal impact design process is initiated by ensuring materials, lighting, and ventilation are viably engaged<ref name=\":1\" />. To make certain that these strategies are fulfilled, the three tactics are approached:\n\n=== Connective process ===\nLWPAC approaches design through connective means, often starting with an [[integrated design]] process.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://intelligent-city.com/|title=Intelligent City \u2013 A Paradigm Shift in Urban Housing|website=Intelligent City|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> This is where the team can work directly with clients to navigate through several stages before finalizing decisions. With the use of [[Interactive design|interactive models]], digital drawings and computations, data can be shared for further design modifications<ref name=\":2\" />. Among all of this, the organization not only begins to confirm the design through a certain level of criteria, but also through methodologies; how it can be executed based on their work schedule. Collectively, the team works together, with engineers and landscape designers, so project changes and improvements can be made early on.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesselitecanada.com/canada-construction-industry/lang-wilson-practice-architecture-culture-lwpac/|title=Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture (LWPAC)|last=bizelite|date=2016-10-07|website=Business Elite Canada Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> LWPAC continues to take on this approach as it simplifies the process, outside of the fixed ideas made in the premature stages<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n=== Generative design ===\nTo manifest a [[Generative design|generative]] attitude towards project designs, LWPAC views innovation as a result of their platform, product and process<ref name=\":2\" />. Through this, the site and the building or installation design can be shared and adaptable, scalable and automated, as well as [[Community design|communal]]<ref name=\":2\" />. With the use of modelling software\u2019s such as [[Building information modeling|BIM]] and digital [[parametric]] tools, specific client needs can be met with a more sustainable attitude<ref name=\":0\" />. LWPAC encourages this format as it explores certain constraints, as well as programmatic designs and explorations<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nLWPAC is known for their [[Intelligent city|Intelligent City]] project which expresses innovative criteria such as: advanced [[Prefabrication|prefabricated]] systems, not only for architectural living but for urban as well<ref name=\":2\" />. They have continued this integration through [[Engineered wood|mass timber]]; for housing and larger development complexes<ref name=\":2\" />. Alongside LWPAC\u2019s knowledge in prefabrication, their shift towards parametric design has maneuvered ways to make buildings more adaptable. This improves sustainability in terms of cost and viability<ref name=\":2\" />.\n\n=== Adaptive control ===\nTo create a shared and adaptable space, LWPAC controls the budget and quality of their work. This is done by neglecting fixed decisions in the premature stages, in order to accommodate for change. The firm responds to this by acknowledging that shifts will occur in the environment, economy and local lifestyle<ref name=\":0\" />. With the use of previously mentioned software\u2019s, budgets can be monitored more closely. This type of close examination carefully controls details regarding materials, construction, client needs and [[feasibility]]<ref name=\":1\" />. Not only does this meet client needs but meets the needs of the urban culture and future<ref name=\":0\" />. LWPAC looks at rising and ongoing issues in order to generate innovative and adaptable designs. It is no surprise that [[global warming]] is a major concern, hence the organization\u2019s emergent use of [[renewable material]]s<ref name=\":3\" />. The firm\u2019s intent is to pay close attention to the community and their individuality in order to deliver sustainable results<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n== Notable projects<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year of Completion\n!Project Name\n!Location\n!Type\n!Description\n|-\n|1999\n|[https://lwpac.net/portfolio/school-of-architecture-utfsm/ School of Architecture], [[Federico Santa Mar\u00eda Technical University|UTFSM]]\n|[[Valpara\u00edso]], Chile\n|[[Modern architecture|Modern Architecture]]; Cultural and Institutional\n|This is a school of architecture which translates [[Cultural heritage|heritage]] architecture into [[Contemporary architecture|contemporary]]. The spaces create a new model for the school as their incompleteness acts as a way for students to interpret the program<ref name=\":1\" />.\n|-\n|2003\n|[https://lwpac.net/portfolio/kang-quan-pavilion/ Kang Quan Pavilion]\n|[[Beijing]], China\n|Cultural and Institutional\n|This [[pavilion]] underwent two main phases, serving as a [[housing unit]] and [[community centre]]. Its passive strategies work in conjunction with the adaptive programming<ref name=\":1\" />.\n|-\n|2003\n|[https://www.canadian-architects.com/en/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc/project/next-lwpac-vancouver-art-gallery Vancouver Art Gallery]\n|[[Vancouver]], Canada\n|Cultural and Institutional\n|An installation that address three main issues; a design that is [[interactive]] through [[Multimedia|multi-media]] and [[multiplicity]]. It is intentionally left incomplete in order for spatial potentials to be freely interpreted by the users; eg., as a sculpture, or a place for seating<ref name=\":0\" />.\n|-\n|2006\n|[https://www.canadian-architects.com/en/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc/project/roar-one ROAR_One]\n|Vancouver, Canada\n|[[Urban design|Urban Living]]\n|The urban living project is meant to address multiple qualities in order to culturally engage the design with the context. It is viewed through multiple lenses in order to reach a solution that tackles the [[diversity]] of the city<ref name=\":0\" />. \n|-\n|2006\n|[https://www.canadian-architects.com/en/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc/project/vanglo-house Vanglo House]\n|Vancouver, Canada\n|Urban Living\n|Vanglo House shares details in the design which take form as an art piece while meeting high sustainable standards<ref name=\":0\" />. \n|-\n|2011\n|[https://www.canadian-architects.com/en/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc/project/monad MONAD]\n|Vancouver, Canada\n|Urban Living\n|'[https://lwpac.net/portfolio/monad/ Platforms for Life]' is a system where housing is promoted as affordable and adaptable. The sustainable prototype engages with digital programming to ensure that high qualities of living needs are met for the community<ref name=\":0\" />. \n|-\n|2015\n|[https://lwpac.net/portfolio/ubc-dairy-research-centre/ UBC Dairy Research Centre Housing]\n|[[Agassiz, British Columbia|Agassiz, Canada]]\n|Cultural and Institutional\n|UBC is a [[Prefabrication|prefabricated]] [[community hub]] for the Agassiz city, welcoming locals and students for housing and social activity. The low-budget project follows LWPAC's intent towards pushing forth sustainable strategies into the design integration<ref name=\":1\" />.\n|}\n\n== Other Projects<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ==\n\n* Museum of Extreme Culture \u2013 [[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler, Canada]] (2002)\n* Colegio Chuquicamata Competition \u2013 [[Calama, Chile]] (2002)\n* Dongli Lake Masterplan \u2013 [[Dongli District|Dongli Lake, China]] (2003)\n* Westside Baptist Church \u2013 Vancouver, Canada (2004)\n* Wallace \u2013 Vancouver, Canada (2008)\n* Historic Precinct Height Study \u2013 [[Downtown Eastside]], Canada (2008)\n* SF House \u2013 Vancouver, Canada (2009)\n* C33 PE House and LWH House \u2013 Vancouver, Canada (2010)\n* Montessori School \u2013 [[Surrey, British Columbia|Surrey, Canada]] (2011)\n* NEXT Gallery \u2013 [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria, Canada]] (Ongoing)\n\n== Awards and recognition<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-architects.com/en/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc/awards|title=LWPAC \u2013 Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture \u2013 Vancouver BC, Canada \u2013 Architects \u2013 Awards|website=World-Architects|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>==\n\n* 2017 [[LafargeHolcim Foundation for Sustainable Construction|Lafarge Holcim]] Silver Award \u2013 ''North America'' \u2013 Platforms for Life <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/international-lafargeholcim-awards-for-sustainable-construction-open-for-entries/|title=International LafargeHolcim Awards for Sustainable Construction open for entries|date=2019-06-18|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lafargeholcim-foundation.org/Awards/regional-lafargeholcim-awards-2017-north-america/winners|title=Winners \u2013 Regional LafargeHolcim Awards 2017 North America|last=info@lafargeholcim-foundation.org|first=LafargeHolcim Foundation for Sustainable Construction|website=LafargeHolcim Foundation website|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2016 Major Research Grant \u2013 [[National Research Council (Canada)|National Research Council ''Canada'']]\n* 2016 Urban Design Award ''City of Vancouver'' \u2013 Vanglo House <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lwpac.net/news/the-vanglo-house-wins-innovation-award-cov-2016-urban-design-awards/|title=Vanglo House wins 'Innovation Award'|date=2016-05-11|website=LWPAC|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2016 10 Best Residences Selection \u2013 [[Azure (magazine)|Azure Magazine]] \u2013 UBC Dairy Research Centre Housing\n* 2014 Urban Design Award ''City of Vancouver'' \u2013 MONAD \u2013 Special Jury Award Excellence and Ingenuity in Architecture <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dwell.com/article/a-modern-multiunit-prefab-prototype-in-vancouver-55fe6124|title=A Modern Multiunit Prefab Prototype in Vancouver|last=Weder|first=Adele|website=Dwell|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2014 Urban Design Award ''City of Vancouver'' \u2013 MONAD \u2013 Medium Scale Residential <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vancouver.ca/home-property-development/urban-design-awards.aspx|title=Urban Design Awards|last=Vancouver|first=City of|website=vancouver.ca|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2013 [[Architectural Institute of British Columbia|AIBC]] Innovation Award \u2013 MONAD <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/rarefied-prefab/|title=Rarefied Prefab|date=2012-12-31|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2013 BC Wood Design Award \u2013 MONAD \u2013 [[Canadian Wood Council]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wood-works.ca/|title=Wood-Works \u2013 Program of the Canadian Wood Council|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* 2012 Western Living Designer \u2013 Architect of the Year Award\n* 2010 Major Grant from Canada Council for the Arts\n* 2008 Governor General\u2019s Medal in Architecture \u2013 ROAR_One\n* 2006 Home of the Year Award \u2013 ROAR_One \u2013 Architecture Magazine ''New York''\n* 2006 Lieutenant Governor\u2019s Medal [[Architectural Institute of British Columbia|Architectural Institute of BC]] Award \u2013 ROAR_One\n* 2006 Lieutenant Governor\u2019s Innovation Award \u2013 ROAR_One\n* 2005 ACSA Faculty Design Award\n* 2005 National Post \u2013 Design Exchange Award\n* 2001 The New Vanguard \u2013 Architectural Record\n* 2000 [[Bienal de Arte de Ponce|Bienal]] Architecture Exhibition \u2013 ''Santiago Chile'' \u2013 School of Architecture \u2013 UTFSM\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=wp7az8ku_gkC \"Exploring Vancouver\"] by Harold D Kalman\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Architecture award winners]]\n[[Category:Architecture firms]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture\n| type = [[Private company]]\n| industry = [[Architecture]], [[urban planning]], [[master planning]]\n| founded = 1999\n| founder = Oliver Lang, Cynthia Wilson\n| hq_location = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada\n| num_employees = 6\n| homepage = https://lwpac.net/\n}}\nThe '''Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture''' (LWPAC) is an [[architectural firm]] founded in 1999 by Oliver Lang and Cynthia Wilson.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.westernliving.ca/architects-of-the-year-lang-wilson|title=Western Living Magazine|last=Mckenzie|first=Kevin Hinton & Ryan|website=Western Living Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> It was first launched in [[New York City]] before being permanently based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], where it evolved into an [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] business.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadian-architects.com/lwpac-lang-wilson-practice-in-architecture-culture-vancouver-bc|title=LWPAC \u2013 Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture \u2013 Vancouver BC, Canada \u2013 Architects -|website=Canadian-Architects|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[Architecture|architectural]] and cultural firm delivers unified resolutions to serve [[Innovation|innovative]] ideas for projects<ref name=\":0\" />. LWPAC works on projects that are large scale; [[urban planning]], and housing complexes, as well as small scale such as [[Installation art|art installations]]<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nLWPAC was co-founded by German-Canadian architect and urban [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]], Oliver Lang, and Canadian designer and cultural entrepreneur, Cindy Wilson.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.westernliving.ca/architects-of-the-year-lang-wilson|title=Practice|last=|first=|date=|website=LWPAC|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> They have worked together in Canada, United States and Germany, to bring-forth a communal and global experience to their projects<ref name=\":1\" />. LWPAC has developed an intent over the years, to serve as a platform for architecture and urban design. Together, this multidisciplinary collaboration forwards [[culture]] as the driving force towards intelligent and [[Innovation|innovative]] designs<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n== Expertise ==\nLWPAC aims to create projects based on their [[Sustainable architecture|sustainable]] outcome through connective, [[Adaptive architecture|adaptable]] and generative ideas<ref name=\":0\" />. They take on a sustainable approach by analyzing urban contexts to ensure passive strategies can be applied to meet low energy demands. A minimal impact design process is initiated by ensuring materials, lighting, and ventilation are viably engaged<ref name=\":1\" />. To make certain that these strategies are fulfilled, the three tactics are approached:\n\n=== Connective process ===\nLWPAC approaches design through connective means, often starting with an [[integrated design]] process.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://intelligent-city.com/|title=Intelligent City \u2013 A Paradigm Shift in Urban Housing|website=Intelligent City|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> This is where the team can work directly with clients to navigate through several stages before finalizing decisions. With the use of [[Interactive design|interactive models]], digital drawings and computations, data can be shared for further design modifications<ref name=\":2\" />. Among all of this, the organization not only begins to confirm the design through a certain level of criteria, but also through methodologies; how it can be executed based on their work schedule. Collectively, the team works together, with engineers and landscape designers, so project changes and improvements can be made early on.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesselitecanada.com/canada-construction-industry/lang-wilson-practice-architecture-culture-lwpac/|title=Lang Wilson Practice in Architecture Culture (LWPAC)|last=bizelite|date=2016-10-07|website=Business Elite Canada Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> LWPAC continues to take on this approach as it simplifies the process, outside of the fixed ideas made in the premature stages<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n=== Generative design ===\nTo manifest a [[Generative design|generative]] attitude towards project designs, LWPAC views innovation as a result of their platform, product and process<ref name=\":2\" />. Through this, the site and the building or installation design can be shared and adaptable, scalable and automated, as well as [[Community design|communal]]<ref name=\":2\" />. With the use of modelling software\u2019s such as [[Building information modeling|BIM]] and digital [[parametric]] tools, specific client needs can be met with a more sustainable attitude<ref name=\":0\" />. LWPAC encourages this format as it explores certain constraints, as well as programmatic designs and explorations<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\nLWPAC is known for their [[Intelligent city|Intelligent City]] project which expresses innovative criteria such as: advanced [[Prefabrication|prefabricated]] systems, not only for architectural living but for urban as well<ref name=\":2\" />. They have continued this integration through [[Engineered wood|mass timber]]; for housing and larger development complexes<ref name=\":2\" />. Alongside LWPAC\u2019s knowledge in prefabrication, their shift towards parametric design has maneuvered ways to make buildings more adaptable. This improves sustainability in terms of cost and viability<ref name=\":2\" />.\n\n=== Adaptive control ===\nTo create a shared and adaptable space, LWPAC controls the budget and quality of their work. This is done by neglecting fixed decisions in the premature stages, in order to accommodate for change. The firm responds to this by acknowledging that shifts will occur in the environment, economy and local lifestyle<ref name=\":0\" />. With the use of previously mentioned software\u2019s, budgets can be monitored more closely. This type of close examination carefully controls details regarding materials, construction, client needs and [[feasibility]]<ref name=\":1\" />. Not only does this meet client needs but meets the needs of the urban culture and future<ref name=\":0\" />. LWPAC looks at rising and ongoing issues in order to generate innovative and adaptable designs. It is no surprise that [[global warming]] is a major concern, hence the organization\u2019s emergent use of [[renewable material]]s<ref name=\":3\" />. The firm\u2019s intent is to pay close attention to the community and their individuality in order to deliver sustainable results<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\n== Notable projects<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year of Completion\n!Project Name\n!Location\n!Type\n!Description\n|-\n|1999\n|[https://lwpac.net/portfolio/school-of-architecture-utfsm/ School of Architecture], [[Federico Santa Mar\u00eda Technical University|UTFSM]]\n|[[Valpara\u00e