{"title_page": "Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex", "text_new": "{{short description|Youngest son of Elizabeth II}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n<!-- ignore your spell-checker: \"Antony\" is the correct spelling -->\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name        = FYI NISHA Prince Demetrius Jacob  \n| title       = [[Earl of Wessex]] ([[#Titles, styles, honours, and arms|more]])\n| image       = Prince Edward February 2015.jpg\n| caption     = The Earl in [[Belfast]], February 2015\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Sophie Rhys-Jones]]|19 June 1999}}\n| issue       = {{plain list|\n* [[Lady Louise Windsor]]\n* [[James, Viscount Severn]]}}\n| full name   = Edward Antony Richard Louis{{efn|Edward does not usually use a family name but when one is needed, it is [[Mountbatten-Windsor]].<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=Royal Households of the United Kingdom#The Royal Household |title=The Royal Family name |work=Official website of the British monarchy|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheRoyalFamilyname/Overview.aspx |accessdate=3 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215182305/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheRoyalFamilyname/Overview.aspx |archivedate=15 February 2009 }}</ref> |group=fn |name=sur}}\n| house       = [[House of Windsor|Windsor]]<!--Don't add [[House of Gl\u00fccksburg]] without prior discussion. See [[Talk:House of Windsor#SHSG Part II]]-->\n| father      = [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n| mother      = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1964|03|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Buckingham Palace]], [[London]], England\n}}\n{{British Royal Family}}\n'''Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex & Forfar''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KGr|GCVO|CD|ADC(P)}} (Edward Antony Richard Louis; born 10 March 1964)<ref name=Buck1>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/page5561.asp |work=Members of The Royal Family |title=TRH The Earl and Countess of Wessex |publisher=Buckingham Palace |accessdate=19 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308203311/http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/page5561.asp |archivedate=8 March 2008 }}</ref> is the youngest of four children and the third son of [[Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]. At the time of his birth, he was third in [[line of succession to the British throne]]; {{as of|2019|7|lc=y|post=,}} he is 11th. The Earl is a full-time working member of the [[British royal family]] and supports the Queen in her official duties \u2013 often alongside his wife, the [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Countess of Wessex]] \u2013 as well as undertaking public engagements for many of his own charities. In particular he has assumed many duties from his father, the Duke of Edinburgh, who retired from public life in 2017. Prince Edward succeeded Prince Philip as president of the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]] (vice-patron since 2006) and opened the [[1990 Commonwealth Games]] in New Zealand and the [[1998 Commonwealth Games]] in Malaysia. He has also taken over the Duke's role in the [[Duke of Edinburgh's Award]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Royal motorcade (8075978363).jpg|thumb|right|Elizabeth II, Prince Philip, [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Prince Andrew]], and Prince Edward\u2014at the opening of the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] in Edmonton, Alberta]]\nPrince Edward was born on 10 March 1964, at [[Buckingham Palace]], [[London]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=43268 |date=11 March 1964 |page=2255 }}</ref> as the third son, and the fourth and youngest child of [[Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]. He was baptised on 2 May 1964 in the private chapel at [[Windsor Castle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englishmonarchs.co.uk/windsor_18.htm|title=Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|accessdate=7 January 2009|work=The House Of Windsor|publisher=English Monarchs|quote=He was baptised on 2 May 1964, at the private chapel at Windsor Castle by the Dean of Windsor and was given the names Edward Anthony Richard Louis.}}</ref> by the [[Dean of Windsor]], [[Robin Woods]].{{efn|Edward's godparents were: [[Prince Richard of Gloucester]] (his mother's cousin); the [[Katharine, Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] (his mother's cousin-in-law, for whom [[Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent]], his mother's aunt, stood proxy); [[Princess George William of Hanover]] (his aunt); the [[Louis, Prince of Hesse and by Rhine|Prince of Hesse and by Rhine]] (his first cousin twice removed); and the [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]] (his uncle).<ref name=\"Yvonne\">{{cite web|url=http://users.uniserve.com/~canyon/christenings.htm#Christenings|title=Yvonne's Royalty Home Page: Royal Christenings|website=users.uniserve.com}}</ref>}}\n\nAs with his older siblings, a [[governess]] was appointed to look after Edward and was responsible for his early education at Buckingham Palace before he attended Gibbs School in Kensington. In September 1972, he joined [[Heatherdown School]], near [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]] in [[Berkshire]]. Later, as his father and elder brothers had done before him, he moved to [[Gordonstoun]], in northern Scotland, and was appointed [[head boy]] in his last term. Edward obtained a C-grade and two D-grades at [[A-level]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The family qualifications|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=16 October 2006|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1531553/The-family-qualifications.html}}</ref> and after leaving school spent a [[gap year]] abroad, working as a house tutor and junior master for two terms at the [[Wanganui Collegiate School]] in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wanganui Collegiate School [Summary]|url=http://www.heritage.org.nz/the-    list/details/9620|website=Heritage New Zealand|accessdate=26 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130112439/http://www.heritage.org.nz/the-list/details/9620|archivedate=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Butterworth|first1=Hugh Montagu|last2=Cooksey [ed.]|first2=Jon|title=Blood and Iron: Letters from the Western Front|date=2011|publisher=Casement|isbn=9781848844919|page=218|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JAlT5D703SAC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=September+1982+at+the+Wanganui+Collegiate+School+in+New+Zealand#v=onepage&q=September%201982%20at%20the%20Wanganui%20Collegiate%20School%20in%20New%20Zealand&f=false}}</ref>\n\nUpon his return to Britain, Edward studied at [[Jesus College, Cambridge]], where he read history. His admission to Cambridge caused some controversy, since his A-level grades were far below the standard normally required for Oxbridge entrance, \"straight As\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The prince with a difference| date=11 June 1999|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/06/99/royal_wedding/363894.stm|work=BBC News}}</ref> Edward graduated in 1986 as [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] ([[British undergraduate degree classification|lower second class honours]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=William enjoys a degree of success|date=12 June 2005|url=http://news.scotsman.com/news/William-enjoys-a-degree-of.2634447.jp|newspaper=The Scotsman|location=Edinburgh|first=Jeremy|last=Watson}}</ref>\n\n==Post-university==\n===Royal Marines===\nIn 1986, on leaving university, Prince Edward joined the [[Royal Marines]], who had paid \u00a312,000 towards his tuition at Cambridge University on condition of future service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/12/world/commando-life-losing-appeal-for-prince.html |title=Commando Life Losing Appeal for Prince? |website=New York Times|date=12 January 1987|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1987, however, Prince Edward dropped out of the gruelling commando course after having completed just one-third of the 12-month training. Media reported that the move prompted a berating from Prince Philip who \"reduced his son to prolonged tears\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20095504,00.html|title=Edward Goes His Own Way |date=26 January 1987 |website=people.com |publisher=People |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> Later, others stated that Philip was in fact the most sympathetic family member and that he understood his son's decision.<ref>{{cite book|first=Ingrid |last=Seward|title=My Husband and I: The Inside Story of 70 Years of the Royal Marriage|year=2017|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-1471159589|chapter=Chapter 9: Watching the Family Grow}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and television===\nAfter leaving the Marines, Edward opted for a career in entertainment. He commissioned the 1986 musical ''[[Cricket (musical)|Cricket]]'' from [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] and [[Tim Rice]], for his mother's 60th birthday celebration, which led to a job offer at Lloyd Webber's [[Really Useful Group|Really Useful Theatre Company]], where he worked as a [[production assistant]] on musicals such as ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', ''[[Starlight Express]]'', and ''[[Cats (musical)|Cats]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-19/entertainment/ca-37020_1_prince-edward-theater |title=Prince Edward Joins the Theater at 'Lowest Rung' |website=LA Times|date=19 January 1988 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> While there he met actress [[Ruthie Henshall]], whom he dated for three years.\n\nEdward's first foray into television production was the programme ''[[The Grand Knockout Tournament]]'', informally known as ''It's a Royal Knockout'', on 15 June 1987, in which four teams sponsored by him, [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]] and the [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Duke]] and [[Sarah, Duchess of York|Duchess of York]] competed for charity. The media attacked the programme; it was later reported that the Queen was not in favour of the event and that her courtiers had all advised against it.<ref>Ben Pimlott [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/royals/readings/polish.html \"Polishing Their Image\"], extract from ''The Queen'', HarperCollins (1996) reprinted on the PBS Frontline webpage</ref>\n\n===Ardent Productions===\nIn 1993, Edward formed the television production company Ardent Productions.<ref name=\"Beckett\">{{cite news|first=Andy|last=Beckett|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/mar/05/themonarchy.broadcasting|title=It's a royal cock-up|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=5 March 2002}}</ref> Ardent was involved in the production of a number of documentaries and dramas,<ref name=\"BFI\">[http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b98a73e44 Ardent Productions Filmography], BFI Film & TV Database</ref> but Edward was accused in the media of using his royal connections for financial gain,<ref>{{cite news|first=Susan|last=Karlin|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/sep/26/entertainment/ca-26454|title=Edward Windsor: Truly a Prince Among Producers|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=26 September 1998}}</ref> and the company was referred to by some industry insiders as \"a sad joke\" due to a perceived lack of professionalism in its operations. [[Andy Beckett]], writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', opined that \"to watch Ardent's few dozen hours of broadcast output is to enter a strange kingdom where every man in Britain still wears a tie, where pieces to camera are done in cricket jumpers, where people clasp their hands behind their backs like guardsmen. Commercial breaks are filled with army recruiting advertisements\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Andy|last=Becket|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/mar/05/themonarchy.broadcasting|title=It's a royal cock-up|newspaper=The Guardian|date=4 March 2002}}</ref>\n\nArdent's productions were somewhat better received in the United States<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/436805.stm|title=Edward: No intention to offend|work=BBC News|date=2 September 1999}}</ref> and a documentary Edward made about his great uncle, [[Edward VIII]] (the late Duke of Windsor) in 1996, sold well worldwide.<ref name=\"BFI\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Summerskill|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/oct/29/broadcasting.society|title=Losses double at Prince's TV firm|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=29 October 2000}}</ref> Nonetheless, the company reported losses every year it operated save one when Edward did not draw a salary.<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> An Ardent two-man film crew was alleged to have invaded the privacy of his nephew [[Prince William]] in September 2001, when he was studying at the [[University of St Andrews]], against industry guidelines regarding the privacy of members of the royal family;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1566416.stm|title=Edward's turbulent media career|work=BBC News|date=27 September 2001}}</ref> William's father, [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], was reportedly angered by the incident.<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Alderson|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1358014/Prince-Edward-to-apologise-to-Queen-and-agrees-to-stop-making-royal-films.html|title=Prince Edward to apologise to Queen and agrees to stop making royal films|newspaper=The Sunday Telegraph|location=London|date=30 September 2001}}</ref> In March 2002, Edward announced that he would step down as production director and joint managing director of Ardent<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> to concentrate on his public duties and to support the Queen during [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Golden Jubilee]] year. Ardent Productions was voluntarily dissolved in June 2009, with assets reduced to just \u00a340.<ref>{{cite news|first=Matthew|last=Moore|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/theroyalfamily/7532309/Prince-Edwards-Ardent-Productions-left-with-assets-of-just-40.html|title=Prince Edward's Ardent Productions left with assets of just \u00a340|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=29 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\n{{main|Wedding of Prince Edward and Sophie Rhys-Jones}}\n[[File:The Earl and Countess of Wessex.JPG|thumb|The Earl and Countess of Wessex at [[Trooping the Colour]] in June 2013]]\nEdward met [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Sophie Rhys-Jones]], then a public relations executive with her own firm, in 1994.<ref name=tom25jul>{{cite news|last=Skyes|first=Tom|title=Sex Lives of the New Royals|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/07/23/sex-lives-of-the-new-royals.html|accessdate=8 June 2013|newspaper=The Daily Beast|date=25 July 2012}}</ref> Their engagement was announced on 6&nbsp;January 1999. Edward proposed to Sophie with an [[Asprey]] and [[Garrard & Co|Garrard]] engagement ring worth an estimated \u00a3105,000: a two-carat oval diamond flanked by two heart-shaped gemstones set in 18-carat white gold.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://royalweddings.helloonline.com/prince-william-and-kate-middleton/galeria/20100922403/kate-middleton/prince-william/rings/1/11/#ancla|title=Crown jewels: The fabulous rings which sealed the love of Europe's royal couples|newspaper=HELLO! magazine|location=UK}}</ref>\n\nTheir wedding took place on 19 June 1999 in [[St George's Chapel at Windsor Castle|St George's Chapel]] at [[Windsor Castle]]. This was a departure from the weddings of his elder brothers, which were large, formal events at [[Westminster Abbey]] or [[St Paul's Cathedral]], and had ended in divorce. On his wedding day, Prince Edward was created [[Earl of Wessex]], with the [[subsidiary title]] of [[Viscount Severn]] (derived from the Welsh roots of the Countess's family),<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55536 |date=28 June 1999 |page=7011 |nolink=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Wessex titles for Edward and Sophie |work=[[BBC News]]| date=19 June 1999|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1999/06/99/royal_wedding/373120.stm | accessdate=3 May 2011}}</ref> breaking from a tradition whereby sons of the sovereign were created [[royal duke]]s. It was however revealed that the Queen wished that he be elevated from [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|the rank of Earl]] to Duke of Edinburgh after that [[duke]]dom, held by [[Prince Philip]] since 1947, reverts to the Crown<ref name=Buck1/> (after the death of the current Duke and the Queen<ref>''[[Whitaker's Almanack]]'' 2010, page 46 'Peers of the Blood Royal'</ref>), and for his children to be [[Lady Louise Windsor#Titles and styles|styled as the children of an Earl]], rather than as ''prince/ss'' and ''royal highness''.<ref name=fam>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5590.asp |title=The Royal Family > Members of the Royal Family > HRH The Earl of Wessex > Marriage and Family |publisher=Buckingham Palace |accessdate=26 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021104848/http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5590.asp |archivedate=21 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife have two children: [[Lady Louise Windsor]], born 8 November 2003, and [[James, Viscount Severn]], born 17 December 2007, They were born at [[Frimley Park Hospital]] in [[Frimley]], They reside at [[Bagshot Park]] in Surrey. While their private residence is Bagshot Park, their office and official London residence is based at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/royal-residences-buckingham-palace|title=Royal Residences: Buckingham Palace|publisher=royal.uk|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n[[File:Edward_Auckland_1992.jpg|thumb|Edward visiting Queen Victoria School for Maori Girls, [[Auckland]], October 1992]]\nThe Earl of Wessex assumed many duties from his father, the Duke of Edinburgh, as he reduced his commitments because of his age. Prince Edward succeeded Prince Philip as president of the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]] (vice-patron since 2006) and opened the [[1990 Commonwealth Games]] in New Zealand and the [[1998 Commonwealth Games]] in Malaysia. He has also taken over the duke's role in the [[Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] Scheme, attending Gold Award ceremonies around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title = The Duke of Edinburgh's Award | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/TheDukeofEdinburghsAward.aspx |work= Royal family | accessdate =29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Britain's Prince Edward, right, shakes hands with U.S. Air Force Brig. Gen. Thomas Deale, the commander of the 451st Air Expeditionary Wing, at Kandahar Airfield in Afghanistan Dec. 20, 2011 111220-F-XH170-474.jpg|thumb|left|The Earl of Wessex in [[Kandahar]], Afghanistan, December 2011]]\nThe Earl and Countess of Wessex established their foundation The Wessex Youth Trust in 1999, with a focus on helping, supporting and advancing registered charities which provide opportunities specifically for children and young people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wessexyouthtrust.org.uk/|title=The Wessex Youth Trust|publisher=wessexyouthtrust.org.uk|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref> His patronages include: the [[British Paralympic Association]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.hellomagazine.com/royalty/201209069223/prince-edward-sophie-paralympic-ball/|title=Earl and Countess of Wessex toast athletes' success at Paralympic Ball|publisher=Hello!|date=6 September 2012|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the International Real Tennis Professionals Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hobarttennis.com.au/2018/02/25/the-2018-real-tennis-challenge-formal-dinner/|title=The 2018 Real Tennis Challenge Formal Dinner|publisher=Hobart Real Tennis Club|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.ca/news/hrh-prince-edward-attend-inaugural-commonwealth-sports-summit.html|title=HRH Prince Edward to attend inaugural Commonwealth Sports Summit|publisher=Common Wealth Games Canada|date=8 September 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/13/battle-britain-may-vs-sturgeon-pictures/commonwealth-games-federation-accompanied-royal-highness-prince/|title=The Battle for Britain: May vs Sturgeon, in pictures|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> [[BadmintonScotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/article/4676/Royal-honour-for-school-sports-stars|title=Royal honour for school sports stars|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|date=2 December 2013|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the [[Tennis and Rackets Association]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/10/who-is-the-biggest-name|title=For a Real Tennis Match, Look to Prince Edward|magazine=Vanity Fair|first=James|last=Zug|date=October 2009|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra and Chorus,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcu.ac.uk/news-events/news/royal-birmingham-conservatoires-opening-concert-a-right-royal-sell-out|title=Royal Birmingham Conservatoire's opening concert a right Royal sell out|publisher=Birmingham City University|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbso.co.uk/news/mirga-meets-our-royal-patron|title=Mirga meets our Royal Patron|publisher=City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra|date=16 June 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> [[London Mozart Players]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swlondoner.co.uk/prince-edward-visits-croydon-for-london-mozart-players-anniversary-concert/|title=Prince Edward visits Croydon for London Mozart Players' anniversary concert|publisher=South West Londoner|first=Rachel|last=Barr|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Haddo House Choral and Operatic Society,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hhcos.org.uk/hhcos/about-us/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Haddo House Choral & Operatic Society|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> [[Northern Ballet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northernballet.com/royal-connexions|title=Royal Connections|publisher=Northern Ballet|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://northernballet.com/blogs/northern-ballet/11-09-30/a-prince-of-england-meets-the-queen-of-the-nile|title=A Prince of England meets the Queen of the Nile|publisher=Northern Ballet|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the [[Edinburgh International Festival]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/prince-edward-takes-up-the-baton-as-edinburgh-festival-patron-tlsr787jp|title=Prince takes up the baton as festival patron|newspaper=The Times|date=12 July 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> and the [[Royal Birmingham Conservatoire]].<ref>[https://www.thecrownchronicles.co.uk/royal-news/earl-countess-wessex/earl-of-wessex-attends-concert-with-julian-lloyd-webber-at-birmingham-conservatoire/ Earl of Wessex attends concert with Julian Lloyd Webber at Birmingham Conservatoire \u2022 The Crown Chronicles<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, the Earl visited Israel in his capacity as chair of the International Council of the [[Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] to attend a number of events organised by the Israel Youth Award program, an affiliate of the Duke of Edinburgh's Award which was founded by his father to recognise adolescents and young adults for completing a series of self-improvement exercises.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel/Prince-Edward-to-arrive-today-1st-royal-visit-in-decade|title=Prince Edward to arrive today; 1st royal visit in decade|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|first=Etgar|last=Lefkovits|date=4 September 2007|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> Edward was himself a recipient of the award's gold medal in 1986 for \"a 60-mile, four-day trek from Blair Atholl to Tomintoul\" that he had planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection/themes/exhibitions/prince-philip-celebrating-ninety-years/windsor-castle-drawings-gallery/the-duke-of-edinburgh-presenting-prince-edward-with-his-gold-award|title=The Duke of Edinburgh presenting Prince Edward with his Gold Award 1986|publisher=Royal Collection Trust|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Edward later went on to become the chair of the Duke of Edinburgh's International Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intaward.org/news/hrh-duke-edinburgh|title=HRH The Duke of Edinburgh|publisher=The Duke of Edinburgh's International Award|date=4 May 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> and has promoted its work on different occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/business/business-news/earl-wessex-duke-edinburghs-award-11958049|title=The Earl of Wessex on why the Duke of Edinburgh's Award scheme is good for business|publisher=Wales Online|first=Sion|last=Barry|date=29 September 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/prince-edward-speaks-at-duke-of-edinburgh-s-international-award-ceremony-1.3647817|title=Prince Edward speaks at Duke of Edinburgh's International Award ceremony|publisher=CBC News|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailytimes.com/news/prince-edward-visits-tennessee-to-promote-duke-of-edinburgh-s/article_7a2225c9-8d6a-5038-a435-055c068e955e.html|title=Prince Edward visits Tennessee to promote Duke of Edinburgh's Award|publisher=The Daily Times|first=Erik|last=Schelzig|date=23 May 2013|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hackney.gov.uk/the-duke-of-edinburghs-award-diamond-anniversary-royally-celebrated-in-hackney/|title=The Duke of Edinburgh's Award Diamond Anniversary royally celebrated in Hackney|publisher=Hackney Council|date=11 November 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In addition to being the chair of the Duke of Edinburgh's International Award Foundation, Edward is also a trustee of the International Award Association, which \"encompasses the DofE UK and all its other 61 National Award Authorities across the globe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brightfuturetrust.org.uk/the-duke-of-edinburgh-award-international-association/|title=The Duke of Edinburgh Award International Association|publisher=Bright Future Trust|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> He was also chair of its international council and in 1999 founded the International Special Projects Group \"to provide a capital fund to broaden the reach of the Award\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jis.gov.jm/government/visits/earl-countess-wessex-visit-jamaica/|title=The Earl and Countess of Wessex to Visit Jamaica [March 2014]|publisher=Jamaica Information Service|year=2014|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Earl of Wessex in 2011 cropped.jpg|thumb|The Earl of Wessex at [[Yate]], Gloucestershire, December 2011]]\nIn June 2011, Edward visited [[Baltimore]] to meet the students and staff of the Living Classrooms Foundation and encourage them to participate in the Duke of Edinburgh's Award's programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/bs-md-ci-prince-edward-visit-20110621-story.html|title=Prince Edward presents city's youth a royal challenge|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|first=Erica|last=Green|date=21 June 2011|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In December 2011, the Earl and Countess of Wessex visited troops in Afghanistan. On the same trip, the royal couple visited [[Bahrain]], and received two gifts of jewels from the Bahraini royal family and Prime Minister. Given concern about human rights abuses in Bahrain, this gift attracted controversy, with calls for the jewels to be sold, and the proceeds used for the benefit of the [[Economy of Bahrain|Bahraini people]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/8999872/How-a-routine-royal-visit-spelt-trouble-for-the-Countess-of-Wessex.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Patrick | last=Sawer | title=How a routine royal visit spelt trouble for the Countess of Wessex | date=8 January 2012}}</ref> In February and March 2012, the couple visited the Caribbean for the Diamond Jubilee. The itinerary consisted of [[Saint Lucia]]; [[Barbados]], [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]]; [[Grenada]]; [[Trinidad and Tobago]]; [[Montserrat]]; [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]; [[Anguilla]]; [[Antigua and Barbuda]]. Highlights included Independence Day celebrations in Saint Lucia,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.thedominican.net/2012/02/royals-to-begin-visit.html | title=Royals to begin Caribbean tour bypasses Dominica|date= 16 February 2012|newspaper= The Dominican|accessdate= 19 February 2012}}</ref> addressing [[Parliament of Barbados|Senate and Assembly of Barbados]] jointly,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/ |first= Sharon |last= Lynch |title= Barbados: Royal Visit To Mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee |date= 27 January 2012 |newspaper= Bajan Sun Online |accessdate= 6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20120719162855/http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/ |archivedate= 19 July 2012 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and a visit to sites affected by the volcanic eruptions in Montserrat.\n\nIn 2013, the couple visited South Africa.<ref name=\"Tel-2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/10469258/Sophie-Wessex-The-unsung-star-of-the-Royal-family.html|title=Sophie Wessex: The unsung star of the Royal family|newspaper=The Telegraph|first=Ingrid|last=Seward|date=23 November 2013}}</ref> The Queen appointed the Earl of Wessex as [[Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland]] for 2014.<ref name=\"Government\">{{Citation | year =2014 | title = The Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland | publisher = Government | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-lord-high-commissioner-to-the-general-assembly-of-the-church-of-scotland-2014}}.</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Edinburgh Gazette |issue=27354 |date=17 January 2014 |page=65 |city=e }}</ref> In 2015, for his contributions to projects associated with badminton, Edward was awarded the President's Medal by the [[Badminton World Federation]] President [[Poul-Erik Hoyer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badmintonscotland.org.uk/news/2015/november/badmintonscotland-patron-hrh-the-earl-of-wessex-honoured-with-bwf-presidents-medal/|title=BADMINTONscotland Patron, HRH The Earl of Wessex honoured with BWF President's Medal|publisher=Badminton Scotland|date=November 2015|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In May 2016, the Earl visited Ghana. Alongside President Mahama, he presented young people with the Head of State Awards for their participation in the Duke of Edinburgh's International Award Scheme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prince-edward-to-visit-ghana-2|title=Prince Edward to visit Ghana|publisher=Gov.uk|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2016, Edward travelled to Chile as a part of the Duke of Edinburgh's Award's diamond anniversary, and visited projects by British and Commonwealth Fire and Rescue Company and Chilean-British Culture University, of which he is an honorary member and patron respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/youth-community-and-service-visit-by-hrh-prince-edward-to-chile|title=Youth, Community and Service; Visit by HRH Prince Edward to Chile|publisher=Gov.uk|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> The Earl and Countess of Wessex represented the Queen at the [[50th Anniversary Celebrations of Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah's Accession to the Throne of Brunei]] in October 2017.<ref name=\"thecrownchronicles.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecrownchronicles.co.uk/royal-news/edward-sophie-attend-sultan-bruneis-golden-jubilee-celebrations/|title=Edward & Sophie attend Sultan of Brunei's Golden Jubilee celebrations|publisher=thecrownchronicles.co.uk|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, the Earl and Countess toured [[Sri Lanka]], participating in the 70th Independence Day celebrations in Colombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/earl-and-countess-wessex-commemorate-sri-lankas-70th-anniversary-independence|title=The Earl and Countess of Wessex commemorate Sri Lanka's 70th Anniversary of Independence|publisher=royal.uk|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.lk/news/Foreign-invitees-to-Independence-Day-Anniversary-celebrations-call-on-President/56-648838 Foreign invitees to Independence Day Anniversary celebrations call on President]</ref> In April 2018, the Earl visited Australia to attend the [[2018 Commonwealth Games|XXI Commonwealth Games]] and attend fundraising events for those participating in the Duke of Edinburgh Award challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/prince-edward-in-town-to-promote-duke-of-edinburghs-international-awards/news-story/d69d1e60ba09909e9e3e305ef1fc5896|title=Prince Edward in town to promote Duke of Edinburgh's International Awards|publisher=The Mercury|date=2 April 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/prince-edward-arrives-in-melbourne-for-duke-of-edinburgh-international-awards-ceremony/news-story/74a8ec19c7c6b54b0b2999567a3c03cb|title=Prince Edward arrives in Melbourne for Duke of Edinburgh International Awards ceremony|publisher=The Weekend Australian|first=Samantha|last=Hutchinson|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter twenty years, the Wessex Youth Trust is reverting to its previous name \u2013 The Earl and Countess of Wessex Charitable Trust \u2013 and will be managed by the Private Office of the Earl and Countess of Wessex. There will be no change to the Trust's broad charitable objectives: it will focus on developing sustainable relationships with a range of selected partner charities and will expand its remit beyond supporting children and young people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wessexyouthtrust.org.uk/index.php|title=Changes to The Wessex Youth Trust|publisher=wessexyouthtrust.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the Earl and Countess visited [[Forfar]] on their first official visit to the town since the Queen granted the Earl the additional title [[Earl of Forfar]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/earl-and-countess-forfar-visit-forfar|title=The Earl and Countess of Forfar visit Forfar|publisher=royal.uk|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> The Earl was presented with 'Earl of Forfar' [[tartan]], which has been designed to celebrate their new titles by town firm the Strathmore Woollen Company. The weave is based on the existing Forfar tartan, which the company designed in 2004 around the colours on the Forfar coat of arms. The geometry remains virtually the same, but the colours have been strengthened, with [[Azure blue]] replaced by the St Andrew's blue of the [[Scottish flag]], and white yarns replaced by a brown to reflect the rich agriculture of the surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/angus-mearns/926177/video-honour-to-be-named-earl-of-forfar-says-prince-edward-as-town-welcomes-him-with-bridies-tartan-and-fiddles/|title=VIDEO: 'Honour' to be named Earl of Forfar says Prince Edward as town welcomes him with bridies, tartan and fiddles|publisher=thecourier.co.uk|accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=RoyalFamily|author=The Royal Family|number=1145699686654853131|date=1 July 2019|title=His Royal Highness is presented with 'Earl of Forfar' tartan, which has been designed for Their Royal Highnesses to celebrate their new titles.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tartanregister.gov.uk/tartanDetails?ref=12595|title=Tartan Details - Earl of Forfar, The|publisher=tartanregister.gov.uk|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n\n===Titles and styles===\n* 10 March 1964 \u2013 19 June 1999: ''His Royal Highness'' The Prince Edward\n* 19 June 1999 \u2013 present: ''His Royal Highness'' The Earl of Wessex<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55536 |date=28 June 1999 |page=7011 }}</ref>\n**in Scotland: 10 March 2019 \u2013 present: ''His Royal Highness'' The Earl of Forfar<ref name=forfar>{{Cite web | url = https://www.royal.uk/title-earl-wessex| title = Title for the Earl of Wessex | publisher = The Royal Family }}</ref><ref name=\"gazette2019\">{{London Gazette |issue=62588 |date=15 March 2019 | page=4737 |endpage= |supp=}}</ref>\nBefore Edward's marriage in 1999, royal commentators conjectured that former royal dukedoms such as [[Duke of Cambridge|Cambridge]] or [[Duke of Sussex|Sussex]] might be granted to him. Instead, the [[Buckingham Palace|Palace]] announced the intention that Prince Edward would eventually be created [[Duke of Edinburgh]], once that title had reverted to The Crown upon the death of both his parents.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/Stylesandtitles.aspx | title = The Earl of Wessex - Styles and titles | publisher = The Royal Family | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904051612/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/Stylesandtitles.aspx |archivedate=4 September 2014}}.</ref>{{efn|The Earl of Wessex would not automatically succeed his father, as titles are passed to the eldest son; hence, the current Prince of Wales would succeed the present Duke. Once the Prince of Wales succeeds to the throne, any titles he has inherited (or will later inherit, if the current Duke is still alive) from his father will merge with the Crown, and he will be free to re-create the Dukedom of Edinburgh}}\n\nOn his marriage in 1999, the prince was ennobled in keeping with tradition, however he was the first prince since the Tudors to be known as an earl rather than a duke (while reserving the rank of duke for the future).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/essential-guide-peerage/ranks-and-privileges-peerage/duke|title=Duke|publisher=[[Debrett's]]|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' reported that he was drawn to the Earldom of Wessex after watching the 1998 film ''[[Shakespeare in Love]]'', in which a character with that title is played by [[Colin Firth]].<ref name= \"EdwardSundayTelegraph\">{{cite web |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8196402/Royal-wedding-Prince-William-asks-the-Queen-not-to-make-him-a-duke.html |title=Royal wedding: Prince William asks the Queen not to make him a duke| first =Richard | last = Eden|date= 12 December 2010 |work= The Telegraph|accessdate= 12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2019, on his 55th birthday, the Earl of Wessex was granted the additional title of [[Earl of Forfar]] for use in Scotland.<ref name=forfar/><ref name=\"gazette2019\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.msn.com/en-ca/lifestyle/lifestyleroyals/the-queen-gives-prince-edward-an-incredible-gift-on-his-birthday/ar-BBUC7fH?ocid=spartandhp |title=The Queen gives Prince Edward an incredible gift on his birthday |first=Hollie |last=Richardson |work=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]] |publisher=[[MSN|msn Lifestyle]] |date=10 March 2019 |access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n{{see also|List of honours of the British royal family by country}}\n\n* [[File:QEII Silver Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 1977: [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2002: [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[Image:Order of the Garter UK ribbon.png|45px]] 23 April 2006: [[Order of the Garter|Royal Knight of the Most Noble Order of the Garter]] (KG)<ref name=\"BuckPress\">{{Cite press release |title=Appointments to the Order of the Garter 2006 |date=23 April 2006 |publisher=Official website of the Royal Family |url=https://www.royal.uk/appointments-order-garter-2006 |quote=The Queen has also been graciously pleased to appoint His Royal Highness The Earl of Wessex, KCVO, to be a Royal Knight Companion of the Most Noble Order of the Garter.}}</ref>\n* [[File:Royal Victorian Order UK ribbon.png|45px]] 10 March 2011: [[Knight Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]] (GCVO)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59724 |date=11 March 2011 |page=4555 |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n** 2 June 2003{{spaced ndash}} 10 March 2011: Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (KCVO)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56951 |date=2 June 2003 |page=6753 |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n** 10 March 1989{{spaced ndash}} 2 June 2003: Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (CVO)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=51673 |date=14 March 1989 |page=3193 |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n* [[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2012: [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]\n\n====Commonwealth====\n* [[File:New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 9 February 1990: [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal|New Zealand Commemorative Medal]]\n* [[File:Saskatchewan Order of Merit ribbon bar 2005.svg|45px]] 11 May 2005: [[Saskatchewan Order of Merit|Honorary Member of the Saskatchewan Order of Merit]] (SOM)<ref name=sask>{{cite press release| title=Prince Edward Awarded Saskatchewan Order of Merit| publisher=Government of Saskatchewan| date=11 May 2005| url=http://www.gov.sk.ca/news?newsId=ca1c6377-29fe-4180-8fc9-3e58b0313f1f| accessdate=27 October 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007012817/http://www.gov.sk.ca/news?newsId=ca1c6377-29fe-4180-8fc9-3e58b0313f1f| archivedate=7 October 2008| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[File:SCM ribbon.png|45px]] 7 June 2005: [[Commemorative Medal for the Centennial of Saskatchewan]]\n* [[File:CD-ribbon.png|45px]] 29 October 2015: [[Canadian Forces Decoration|Canadian Forces' Decoration]]<ref>{{Citation |title=Honours & recognition for the men and women of the Canadian Forces 2015 |url=http://publications.gc.ca/collections/collection_2016/mdn-dnd/D3-23-2015-eng.pdf |work=Department of National Defence |page=28}}</ref>\n* [[File:Sultan's Golden Jubilee Medal (2017).jpg|45px]] 5 October 2017: Sultan of Brunei Golden Jubilee Medal<ref>{{cite tweet|user=RoyalFamily|author=The Royal Family|number=915958265103732736|date=5 October 2017|title=The Earl and Countess of Wessex are in Brunei to attend The Sultan of Brunei's Golden Jubilee celebrations.}}</ref><ref name=\"thecrownchronicles.co.uk\"/>\n\n====Military appointments====\n* October 1986{{spaced ndash}}January 1987: [[Officer Cadet]], [[Royal Marines]]\n* 1 August 2004{{spaced ndash}}present: [[Personal Aide-de-Camp|Personal Aide-de-Camp to Her Majesty The Queen]] (AdC(P))\n\n=====Honorary military appointments=====\n;{{Flagicon|CAN}} Canada\n* 2002: [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of [[the Hastings and Prince Edward Regiment]]\n* 2003: Colonel-in-Chief of the [[Saskatchewan Dragoons]]\n* 2005: Colonel-in-Chief of [[the Prince Edward Island Regiment]]\n* 2007: Honorary Deputy Commissioner of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n\n;{{Flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n[[File:Prince Edward 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Prince Edward wearing the barrack dress uniform of in [[The Rifles]] in the rank of [[colonel]] (2014)]]\n* 2003: Royal [[Honorary Colonel]] of the [[Royal Wessex Yeomanry]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57032 |date=19 August 2003 |page=10318 |supp=y |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n* 2006: [[Commodore-in-Chief]] of the [[Royal Fleet Auxiliary]]\n* 2007: Royal Colonel of 2nd Battalion, [[The Rifles]]\n* 2008: [[Honorary Air Commodore]] of [[Royal Air Force Waddington]]\n* 2011: Royal Honorary Colonel of the [[London Regiment (1993)|London Regiment]]<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59772 |date=3 May 2011 |page=8211 |supp=y |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n\n====Civic appointments====\n* 2008: [[Liveryman]] ''[[Honoris Causa]]'', [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers]]\n* 2008: [[Liveryman]] ''[[Honoris Causa]]'', [[Worshipful Company of Gardeners]]\n* 2011: [[Freedom of the City of London|Freeman]] of the [[City of London]]\n* 2011: Member, [[Court of Assistants]], [[Worshipful Company of Haberdashers]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/Honoursandappointments.aspx|title=The Earl of Wessex: Honours and appointments|publisher=Royal Household}}</ref>\n* 2011: Member, [[Court of Assistants]], [[Worshipful Company of Gardeners]]\n* 2013: [[Master craftsman|Master]], [[Worshipful Company of Gardeners]]\n* 2014: [[Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland|Lord High Commissioner]], [[General Assembly of the Church of Scotland]]<ref>[http://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-lord-high-commissioner-to-the-general-assembly-of-the-church-of-scotland-2014 Number 10 \u2013 Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland 2014] (accessed 8 December 2013)</ref>\n\n====Academic appointments====\n* 2013 \u2013 present: [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Bath]]<ref name=Bath>{{cite web|title=The Chancellor|url=http://www.bath.ac.uk/about/organisation/chancellor/|accessdate=7 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n;Honorary degrees\n* 1991: [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|Master of Arts]], [[University of Cambridge]]\n* 1994: Honorary [[Doctor of Laws]], [[University of Victoria]]\n* 2007: Honorary [[Doctor of Laws]], [[University of Prince Edward Island]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Prince Edward gives medals to P.E.I. soldiers|publisher=CTV|date=14 October 2007|url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071014/prince_071014/20071014?hub=TopStories&s_name=|accessdate=11 July 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130041857/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071014/prince_071014/20071014?hub=TopStories|archivedate=30 November 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* 2013: Honorary [[Doctor of Laws]], [[University of Bath]]<ref name=\"Bath\"/>\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|name           = the Earl of Wessex\n|image          = Coat of Arms of Edward, Earl of Wessex.svg\n|bannerimage    = Royal Standard of Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex.svg\n|badgeimage     =\n|notes          = The Earl's personal [[coat of arms]] is that of the [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom]] with a label for difference\n|year_adopted   = 1983\n|coronet        = The [[coronet]] of a son of the sovereign Proper, thereon a lion statant gardant Or crowned of the same coronet charged with a label as in the arms.\n|crest          =\n|torse          =\n|helm           =\n|escutcheon     = Quarterly, 1st and 4th Gules three lions passant guardant in pale Or armed and langed Azure, 2nd Or a lion rampant Gules armed and langued Azure within a double tressure flory counterflory of the Second, 3rd Azure a harp Or stringed Argent\n|supporters     = Dexter, a lion rampant gardant Or imperially crowned Proper; Sinister, a unicorn Argent, armed, crined and unguled Or, gorged with a coronet Or composed of crosses patt\u00e9es and fleurs de lis a chain affixed thereto passing between the forelegs and reflexed over the back also Or\n|compartment    =\n|motto          = The Order of the Garter circlet.<br />'''[[Honi soit qui mal y pense]]'''<br />''(Shame be to him who thinks evil of it)''\n|orders         =\n|other_elements = The whole differenced by a label of three points Argent the central point charged with a [[Tudor rose]].\n|banner         = The [[Royal Standard of the United Kingdom]] labelled for difference as in his arms. (In Scotland: [[File:Royal Standard of Prince Edward, Earl of Forfar.svg|50px]])\n|badge          =\n|symbolism      = As with the Royal Arms of the United Kingdom. The first and fourth quarters are the arms of England, the second of Scotland, the third of Ireland.}}\n\n===Personal flag for Canada===\n{{Main|Royal standards of Canada#Other members of the Royal Family}}\n[[File:Royal Standard of Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex (in Canada).svg|thumb|Flag of the Earl of Wessex for use in Canada]]\n\nSince 2014, the Earl of Wessex has a personal [[heraldic flag]] for use in Canada. It is the [[Royal Arms of Canada]] in [[banner of arms|banner form]] defaced with a blue [[roundel (heraldry)|roundel]] surrounded by a wreath of gold maple leaves, within which is a depiction of an ''\"E\"'' surmounted by a coronet. Above the roundel is a white [[Label (heraldry)|label]] of three points, the centre one charged with a Tudor rose.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Flags of the Royal Family|url=http://canadiancrown.gc.ca/eng/1396525887776|website=Canadian Crown|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://reg.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=2531 | title=The Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex | publisher=Office of the Governor General of Canada: Canadian Heraldic Authority | work=Public Register of Arms, Flags and Badges | accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center |ref=<ref>{{Cite book |last=Paget |first=Gerald|title=The Lineage and Ancestry of H.R.H. Prince Charles, Prince of Wales ''(2 vols)'' |location=Edinburgh |publisher=Charles Skilton |year=1977 |isbn=978-0-284-40016-1}}</ref>\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Prince Philip of Greece and Denmark]]\n|3= 3. [[Elizabeth II|Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom]]\n|4= 4. [[Prince Andrew of Greece and Denmark]]\n|5= 5. [[Princess Alice of Battenberg]]\n|6= 6. [[George VI|George VI of the United Kingdom]]\n|7= 7. [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Lady Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon]]\n|8= 8. [[George I of Greece]]\n|9= 9. [[Olga Constantinovna of Russia|Grand Duchess Olga Constantinovna of Russia]]\n|10= 10. [[Prince Louis of Battenberg]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Victoria of Hesse and by Rhine]]\n|12= 12. [[George V|George V of the United Kingdom]]\n|13= 13. [[Mary of Teck|Princess Mary of Teck]]\n|14= 14. [[Claude Bowes-Lyon, 14th Earl of Strathmore and Kinghorne]]\n|15= 15. [[Cecilia Bowes-Lyon, Countess of Strathmore and Kinghorne|Cecilia Cavendish-Bentinck]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of British princes]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=fn}}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Spoken Wikipedia|En-Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex-article.ogg|12 July 2014}}\n{{Commons category|Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/the-earl-of-wessex |title=The Earl of Wessex|publisher=at the Royal Family website}}\n* {{Britannica|639997|Prince Edward, earl of Wessex}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0921844|name=Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Windsor]]|10 March|1964}}\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Princess Eugenie, Mrs Jack Brooksbank]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Succession to the British throne]]|years=11th in line}}\n{{S-fol|after=[[James, Viscount Severn|Viscount Severn]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-new|rows=2|creation}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Earl of Wessex]]|years=1999\u2013present}}\n{{S-inc|rows=2|heir=[[James, Viscount Severn]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Earl of Forfar]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{S-prec|uk}}\n{{S-bef|rows=2|before=[[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|The Duke of York]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom#British royal family|Gentlemen]]<br />''The Earl of Wessex''}}\n{{S-fol|after=[[Prince William, Duke of Cambridge|The Duke of Cambridge]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom#British royal family|Gentlemen]]<br />'''''in [[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom#Current practice|current practice]]''}}\n{{S-fol|after=[[Prince Henry, Duke of Sussex|The Duke of Sussex]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Christopher Tugendhat, Baron Tugendhat|The Lord Tugendhat]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[University of Bath|Chancellor of the University of Bath]]|years=2013\u2013present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Gentlemen)|Edward, Earl of Wessex, Prince}}\n{{British princes}}\n{{Current British earls}}\n{{Members of the Order of the Garter}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wessex, Prince Edward, Earl of}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Anglicans]]\n[[Category:British television presenters]]\n[[Category:British television producers]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Bath]]\n[[Category:Earls of Wessex]]\n[[Category:Earls of Forfar]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor|Edward, Earl of Wessex]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Garter]]\n[[Category:Members of the Saskatchewan Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Mountbatten-Windsor family|Edward]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gibbs School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gordonstoun]]\n[[Category:People educated at Heatherdown School]]\n[[Category:People from Westminster]]\n[[Category:Princes of the United Kingdom|Edward]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Nation (Antigua and Barbuda)]]\n[[Category:Royal Marines officers]]\n[[Category:Honorary air commodores]]\n[[Category:Earls in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Youngest son of Elizabeth II}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n<!-- ignore your spell-checker: \"Antony\" is the correct spelling -->\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name        = Prince Edward\n| title       = [[Earl of Wessex]] ([[#Titles, styles, honours, and arms|more]])\n| image       = Prince Edward February 2015.jpg\n| caption     = The Earl in [[Belfast]], February 2015\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Sophie Rhys-Jones]]|19 June 1999}}\n| issue       = {{plain list|\n* [[Lady Louise Windsor]]\n* [[James, Viscount Severn]]}}\n| full name   = Edward Antony Richard Louis{{efn|Edward does not usually use a family name but when one is needed, it is [[Mountbatten-Windsor]].<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=Royal Households of the United Kingdom#The Royal Household |title=The Royal Family name |work=Official website of the British monarchy|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheRoyalFamilyname/Overview.aspx |accessdate=3 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215182305/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheRoyalFamilyname/Overview.aspx |archivedate=15 February 2009 }}</ref> |group=fn |name=sur}}\n| house       = [[House of Windsor|Windsor]]<!--Don't add [[House of Gl\u00fccksburg]] without prior discussion. See [[Talk:House of Windsor#SHSG Part II]]-->\n| father      = [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]\n| mother      = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1964|03|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Buckingham Palace]], [[London]], England\n}}\n{{British Royal Family}}\n'''Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex & Forfar''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|KGr|GCVO|CD|ADC(P)}} (Edward Antony Richard Louis; born 10 March 1964)<ref name=Buck1>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/page5561.asp |work=Members of The Royal Family |title=TRH The Earl and Countess of Wessex |publisher=Buckingham Palace |accessdate=19 March 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308203311/http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/page5561.asp |archivedate=8 March 2008 }}</ref> is the youngest of four children and the third son of [[Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]. At the time of his birth, he was third in [[line of succession to the British throne]]; {{as of|2019|7|lc=y|post=,}} he is 11th. The Earl is a full-time working member of the [[British royal family]] and supports the Queen in her official duties \u2013 often alongside his wife, the [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Countess of Wessex]] \u2013 as well as undertaking public engagements for many of his own charities. In particular he has assumed many duties from his father, the Duke of Edinburgh, who retired from public life in 2017. Prince Edward succeeded Prince Philip as president of the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]] (vice-patron since 2006) and opened the [[1990 Commonwealth Games]] in New Zealand and the [[1998 Commonwealth Games]] in Malaysia. He has also taken over the Duke's role in the [[Duke of Edinburgh's Award]].\n\n==Early life and education==\n[[File:Royal motorcade (8075978363).jpg|thumb|right|Elizabeth II, Prince Philip, [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Prince Andrew]], and Prince Edward\u2014at the opening of the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] in Edmonton, Alberta]]\nPrince Edward was born on 10 March 1964, at [[Buckingham Palace]], [[London]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=43268 |date=11 March 1964 |page=2255 }}</ref> as the third son, and the fourth and youngest child of [[Elizabeth II]] and [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]]. He was baptised on 2 May 1964 in the private chapel at [[Windsor Castle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.englishmonarchs.co.uk/windsor_18.htm|title=Prince Edward, Earl of Wessex|accessdate=7 January 2009|work=The House Of Windsor|publisher=English Monarchs|quote=He was baptised on 2 May 1964, at the private chapel at Windsor Castle by the Dean of Windsor and was given the names Edward Anthony Richard Louis.}}</ref> by the [[Dean of Windsor]], [[Robin Woods]].{{efn|Edward's godparents were: [[Prince Richard of Gloucester]] (his mother's cousin); the [[Katharine, Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] (his mother's cousin-in-law, for whom [[Princess Marina, Duchess of Kent]], his mother's aunt, stood proxy); [[Princess George William of Hanover]] (his aunt); the [[Louis, Prince of Hesse and by Rhine|Prince of Hesse and by Rhine]] (his first cousin twice removed); and the [[Antony Armstrong-Jones, 1st Earl of Snowdon|Earl of Snowdon]] (his uncle).<ref name=\"Yvonne\">{{cite web|url=http://users.uniserve.com/~canyon/christenings.htm#Christenings|title=Yvonne's Royalty Home Page: Royal Christenings|website=users.uniserve.com}}</ref>}}\n\nAs with his older siblings, a [[governess]] was appointed to look after Edward and was responsible for his early education at Buckingham Palace before he attended Gibbs School in Kensington. In September 1972, he joined [[Heatherdown School]], near [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]] in [[Berkshire]]. Later, as his father and elder brothers had done before him, he moved to [[Gordonstoun]], in northern Scotland, and was appointed [[head boy]] in his last term. Edward obtained a C-grade and two D-grades at [[A-level]],<ref>{{cite news|title=The family qualifications|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=16 October 2006|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1531553/The-family-qualifications.html}}</ref> and after leaving school spent a [[gap year]] abroad, working as a house tutor and junior master for two terms at the [[Wanganui Collegiate School]] in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wanganui Collegiate School [Summary]|url=http://www.heritage.org.nz/the-    list/details/9620|website=Heritage New Zealand|accessdate=26 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130112439/http://www.heritage.org.nz/the-list/details/9620|archivedate=January 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Butterworth|first1=Hugh Montagu|last2=Cooksey [ed.]|first2=Jon|title=Blood and Iron: Letters from the Western Front|date=2011|publisher=Casement|isbn=9781848844919|page=218|url=https://books.google.com/?id=JAlT5D703SAC&pg=PA218&lpg=PA218&dq=September+1982+at+the+Wanganui+Collegiate+School+in+New+Zealand#v=onepage&q=September%201982%20at%20the%20Wanganui%20Collegiate%20School%20in%20New%20Zealand&f=false}}</ref>\n\nUpon his return to Britain, Edward studied at [[Jesus College, Cambridge]], where he read history. His admission to Cambridge caused some controversy, since his A-level grades were far below the standard normally required for Oxbridge entrance, \"straight As\".<ref>{{cite news|title=The prince with a difference| date=11 June 1999|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/06/99/royal_wedding/363894.stm|work=BBC News}}</ref> Edward graduated in 1986 as [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] ([[British undergraduate degree classification|lower second class honours]]).<ref>{{cite news|title=William enjoys a degree of success|date=12 June 2005|url=http://news.scotsman.com/news/William-enjoys-a-degree-of.2634447.jp|newspaper=The Scotsman|location=Edinburgh|first=Jeremy|last=Watson}}</ref>\n\n==Post-university==\n===Royal Marines===\nIn 1986, on leaving university, Prince Edward joined the [[Royal Marines]], who had paid \u00a312,000 towards his tuition at Cambridge University on condition of future service.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/01/12/world/commando-life-losing-appeal-for-prince.html |title=Commando Life Losing Appeal for Prince? |website=New York Times|date=12 January 1987|accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1987, however, Prince Edward dropped out of the gruelling commando course after having completed just one-third of the 12-month training. Media reported that the move prompted a berating from Prince Philip who \"reduced his son to prolonged tears\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20095504,00.html|title=Edward Goes His Own Way |date=26 January 1987 |website=people.com |publisher=People |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> Later, others stated that Philip was in fact the most sympathetic family member and that he understood his son's decision.<ref>{{cite book|first=Ingrid |last=Seward|title=My Husband and I: The Inside Story of 70 Years of the Royal Marriage|year=2017|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=978-1471159589|chapter=Chapter 9: Watching the Family Grow}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre and television===\nAfter leaving the Marines, Edward opted for a career in entertainment. He commissioned the 1986 musical ''[[Cricket (musical)|Cricket]]'' from [[Andrew Lloyd Webber]] and [[Tim Rice]], for his mother's 60th birthday celebration, which led to a job offer at Lloyd Webber's [[Really Useful Group|Really Useful Theatre Company]], where he worked as a [[production assistant]] on musicals such as ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'', ''[[Starlight Express]]'', and ''[[Cats (musical)|Cats]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-01-19/entertainment/ca-37020_1_prince-edward-theater |title=Prince Edward Joins the Theater at 'Lowest Rung' |website=LA Times|date=19 January 1988 |accessdate=10 January 2014}}</ref> While there he met actress [[Ruthie Henshall]], whom he dated for three years.\n\nEdward's first foray into television production was the programme ''[[The Grand Knockout Tournament]]'', informally known as ''It's a Royal Knockout'', on 15 June 1987, in which four teams sponsored by him, [[Anne, Princess Royal|Princess Anne]] and the [[Prince Andrew, Duke of York|Duke]] and [[Sarah, Duchess of York|Duchess of York]] competed for charity. The media attacked the programme; it was later reported that the Queen was not in favour of the event and that her courtiers had all advised against it.<ref>Ben Pimlott [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/royals/readings/polish.html \"Polishing Their Image\"], extract from ''The Queen'', HarperCollins (1996) reprinted on the PBS Frontline webpage</ref>\n\n===Ardent Productions===\nIn 1993, Edward formed the television production company Ardent Productions.<ref name=\"Beckett\">{{cite news|first=Andy|last=Beckett|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/mar/05/themonarchy.broadcasting|title=It's a royal cock-up|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=5 March 2002}}</ref> Ardent was involved in the production of a number of documentaries and dramas,<ref name=\"BFI\">[http://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b98a73e44 Ardent Productions Filmography], BFI Film & TV Database</ref> but Edward was accused in the media of using his royal connections for financial gain,<ref>{{cite news|first=Susan|last=Karlin|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1998/sep/26/entertainment/ca-26454|title=Edward Windsor: Truly a Prince Among Producers|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=26 September 1998}}</ref> and the company was referred to by some industry insiders as \"a sad joke\" due to a perceived lack of professionalism in its operations. [[Andy Beckett]], writing in ''[[The Guardian]]'', opined that \"to watch Ardent's few dozen hours of broadcast output is to enter a strange kingdom where every man in Britain still wears a tie, where pieces to camera are done in cricket jumpers, where people clasp their hands behind their backs like guardsmen. Commercial breaks are filled with army recruiting advertisements\".<ref>{{cite news|first=Andy|last=Becket|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2002/mar/05/themonarchy.broadcasting|title=It's a royal cock-up|newspaper=The Guardian|date=4 March 2002}}</ref>\n\nArdent's productions were somewhat better received in the United States<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/436805.stm|title=Edward: No intention to offend|work=BBC News|date=2 September 1999}}</ref> and a documentary Edward made about his great uncle, [[Edward VIII]] (the late Duke of Windsor) in 1996, sold well worldwide.<ref name=\"BFI\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Summerskill|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2000/oct/29/broadcasting.society|title=Losses double at Prince's TV firm|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=29 October 2000}}</ref> Nonetheless, the company reported losses every year it operated save one when Edward did not draw a salary.<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> An Ardent two-man film crew was alleged to have invaded the privacy of his nephew [[Prince William]] in September 2001, when he was studying at the [[University of St Andrews]], against industry guidelines regarding the privacy of members of the royal family;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/1566416.stm|title=Edward's turbulent media career|work=BBC News|date=27 September 2001}}</ref> William's father, [[Charles, Prince of Wales]], was reportedly angered by the incident.<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Alderson|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1358014/Prince-Edward-to-apologise-to-Queen-and-agrees-to-stop-making-royal-films.html|title=Prince Edward to apologise to Queen and agrees to stop making royal films|newspaper=The Sunday Telegraph|location=London|date=30 September 2001}}</ref> In March 2002, Edward announced that he would step down as production director and joint managing director of Ardent<ref name=\"Beckett\"/> to concentrate on his public duties and to support the Queen during [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|her Golden Jubilee]] year. Ardent Productions was voluntarily dissolved in June 2009, with assets reduced to just \u00a340.<ref>{{cite news|first=Matthew|last=Moore|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/theroyalfamily/7532309/Prince-Edwards-Ardent-Productions-left-with-assets-of-just-40.html|title=Prince Edward's Ardent Productions left with assets of just \u00a340|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|date=29 March 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Marriage==\n{{main|Wedding of Prince Edward and Sophie Rhys-Jones}}\n[[File:The Earl and Countess of Wessex.JPG|thumb|The Earl and Countess of Wessex at [[Trooping the Colour]] in June 2013]]\nEdward met [[Sophie, Countess of Wessex|Sophie Rhys-Jones]], then a public relations executive with her own firm, in 1994.<ref name=tom25jul>{{cite news|last=Skyes|first=Tom|title=Sex Lives of the New Royals|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/07/23/sex-lives-of-the-new-royals.html|accessdate=8 June 2013|newspaper=The Daily Beast|date=25 July 2012}}</ref> Their engagement was announced on 6&nbsp;January 1999. Edward proposed to Sophie with an [[Asprey]] and [[Garrard & Co|Garrard]] engagement ring worth an estimated \u00a3105,000: a two-carat oval diamond flanked by two heart-shaped gemstones set in 18-carat white gold.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://royalweddings.helloonline.com/prince-william-and-kate-middleton/galeria/20100922403/kate-middleton/prince-william/rings/1/11/#ancla|title=Crown jewels: The fabulous rings which sealed the love of Europe's royal couples|newspaper=HELLO! magazine|location=UK}}</ref>\n\nTheir wedding took place on 19 June 1999 in [[St George's Chapel at Windsor Castle|St George's Chapel]] at [[Windsor Castle]]. This was a departure from the weddings of his elder brothers, which were large, formal events at [[Westminster Abbey]] or [[St Paul's Cathedral]], and had ended in divorce. On his wedding day, Prince Edward was created [[Earl of Wessex]], with the [[subsidiary title]] of [[Viscount Severn]] (derived from the Welsh roots of the Countess's family),<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55536 |date=28 June 1999 |page=7011 |nolink=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title=Wessex titles for Edward and Sophie |work=[[BBC News]]| date=19 June 1999|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1999/06/99/royal_wedding/373120.stm | accessdate=3 May 2011}}</ref> breaking from a tradition whereby sons of the sovereign were created [[royal duke]]s. It was however revealed that the Queen wished that he be elevated from [[Peerage of the United Kingdom|the rank of Earl]] to Duke of Edinburgh after that [[duke]]dom, held by [[Prince Philip]] since 1947, reverts to the Crown<ref name=Buck1/> (after the death of the current Duke and the Queen<ref>''[[Whitaker's Almanack]]'' 2010, page 46 'Peers of the Blood Royal'</ref>), and for his children to be [[Lady Louise Windsor#Titles and styles|styled as the children of an Earl]], rather than as ''prince/ss'' and ''royal highness''.<ref name=fam>{{cite web|url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5590.asp |title=The Royal Family > Members of the Royal Family > HRH The Earl of Wessex > Marriage and Family |publisher=Buckingham Palace |accessdate=26 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021104848/http://www.royal.gov.uk/output/Page5590.asp |archivedate=21 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\nHe and his wife have two children: [[Lady Louise Windsor]], born 8 November 2003, and [[James, Viscount Severn]], born 17 December 2007, They were born at [[Frimley Park Hospital]] in [[Frimley]], They reside at [[Bagshot Park]] in Surrey. While their private residence is Bagshot Park, their office and official London residence is based at [[Buckingham Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/royal-residences-buckingham-palace|title=Royal Residences: Buckingham Palace|publisher=royal.uk|accessdate=21 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Activities==\n[[File:Edward_Auckland_1992.jpg|thumb|Edward visiting Queen Victoria School for Maori Girls, [[Auckland]], October 1992]]\nThe Earl of Wessex assumed many duties from his father, the Duke of Edinburgh, as he reduced his commitments because of his age. Prince Edward succeeded Prince Philip as president of the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]] (vice-patron since 2006) and opened the [[1990 Commonwealth Games]] in New Zealand and the [[1998 Commonwealth Games]] in Malaysia. He has also taken over the duke's role in the [[Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] Scheme, attending Gold Award ceremonies around the world.<ref>{{cite web|title = The Duke of Edinburgh's Award | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/TheDukeofEdinburghsAward.aspx |work= Royal family | accessdate =29 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Britain's Prince Edward, right, shakes hands with U.S. Air Force Brig. Gen. Thomas Deale, the commander of the 451st Air Expeditionary Wing, at Kandahar Airfield in Afghanistan Dec. 20, 2011 111220-F-XH170-474.jpg|thumb|left|The Earl of Wessex in [[Kandahar]], Afghanistan, December 2011]]\nThe Earl and Countess of Wessex established their foundation The Wessex Youth Trust in 1999, with a focus on helping, supporting and advancing registered charities which provide opportunities specifically for children and young people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wessexyouthtrust.org.uk/|title=The Wessex Youth Trust|publisher=wessexyouthtrust.org.uk|accessdate=9 May 2018}}</ref> His patronages include: the [[British Paralympic Association]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://us.hellomagazine.com/royalty/201209069223/prince-edward-sophie-paralympic-ball/|title=Earl and Countess of Wessex toast athletes' success at Paralympic Ball|publisher=Hello!|date=6 September 2012|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the International Real Tennis Professionals Association,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hobarttennis.com.au/2018/02/25/the-2018-real-tennis-challenge-formal-dinner/|title=The 2018 Real Tennis Challenge Formal Dinner|publisher=Hobart Real Tennis Club|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the [[Commonwealth Games Federation]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.ca/news/hrh-prince-edward-attend-inaugural-commonwealth-sports-summit.html|title=HRH Prince Edward to attend inaugural Commonwealth Sports Summit|publisher=Common Wealth Games Canada|date=8 September 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/13/battle-britain-may-vs-sturgeon-pictures/commonwealth-games-federation-accompanied-royal-highness-prince/|title=The Battle for Britain: May vs Sturgeon, in pictures|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 March 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> [[BadmintonScotland]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastrenfrewshire.gov.uk/article/4676/Royal-honour-for-school-sports-stars|title=Royal honour for school sports stars|publisher=East Renfrewshire Council|date=2 December 2013|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the [[Tennis and Rackets Association]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2009/10/who-is-the-biggest-name|title=For a Real Tennis Match, Look to Prince Edward|magazine=Vanity Fair|first=James|last=Zug|date=October 2009|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra and Chorus,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcu.ac.uk/news-events/news/royal-birmingham-conservatoires-opening-concert-a-right-royal-sell-out|title=Royal Birmingham Conservatoire's opening concert a right Royal sell out|publisher=Birmingham City University|date=13 March 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbso.co.uk/news/mirga-meets-our-royal-patron|title=Mirga meets our Royal Patron|publisher=City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra|date=16 June 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> [[London Mozart Players]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.swlondoner.co.uk/prince-edward-visits-croydon-for-london-mozart-players-anniversary-concert/|title=Prince Edward visits Croydon for London Mozart Players' anniversary concert|publisher=South West Londoner|first=Rachel|last=Barr|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Haddo House Choral and Operatic Society,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hhcos.org.uk/hhcos/about-us/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Haddo House Choral & Operatic Society|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> [[Northern Ballet]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://northernballet.com/royal-connexions|title=Royal Connections|publisher=Northern Ballet|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://northernballet.com/blogs/northern-ballet/11-09-30/a-prince-of-england-meets-the-queen-of-the-nile|title=A Prince of England meets the Queen of the Nile|publisher=Northern Ballet|date=30 September 2011|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> the [[Edinburgh International Festival]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/prince-edward-takes-up-the-baton-as-edinburgh-festival-patron-tlsr787jp|title=Prince takes up the baton as festival patron|newspaper=The Times|date=12 July 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> and the [[Royal Birmingham Conservatoire]].<ref>[https://www.thecrownchronicles.co.uk/royal-news/earl-countess-wessex/earl-of-wessex-attends-concert-with-julian-lloyd-webber-at-birmingham-conservatoire/ Earl of Wessex attends concert with Julian Lloyd Webber at Birmingham Conservatoire \u2022 The Crown Chronicles<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn September 2007, the Earl visited Israel in his capacity as chair of the International Council of the [[Duke of Edinburgh's Award]] to attend a number of events organised by the Israel Youth Award program, an affiliate of the Duke of Edinburgh's Award which was founded by his father to recognise adolescents and young adults for completing a series of self-improvement exercises.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.jpost.com/Israel/Prince-Edward-to-arrive-today-1st-royal-visit-in-decade|title=Prince Edward to arrive today; 1st royal visit in decade|newspaper=Jerusalem Post|first=Etgar|last=Lefkovits|date=4 September 2007|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> Edward was himself a recipient of the award's gold medal in 1986 for \"a 60-mile, four-day trek from Blair Atholl to Tomintoul\" that he had planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royalcollection.org.uk/collection/themes/exhibitions/prince-philip-celebrating-ninety-years/windsor-castle-drawings-gallery/the-duke-of-edinburgh-presenting-prince-edward-with-his-gold-award|title=The Duke of Edinburgh presenting Prince Edward with his Gold Award 1986|publisher=Royal Collection Trust|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> Edward later went on to become the chair of the Duke of Edinburgh's International Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intaward.org/news/hrh-duke-edinburgh|title=HRH The Duke of Edinburgh|publisher=The Duke of Edinburgh's International Award|date=4 May 2017|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> and has promoted its work on different occasions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walesonline.co.uk/business/business-news/earl-wessex-duke-edinburghs-award-11958049|title=The Earl of Wessex on why the Duke of Edinburgh's Award scheme is good for business|publisher=Wales Online|first=Sion|last=Barry|date=29 September 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/manitoba/prince-edward-speaks-at-duke-of-edinburgh-s-international-award-ceremony-1.3647817|title=Prince Edward speaks at Duke of Edinburgh's International Award ceremony|publisher=CBC News|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailytimes.com/news/prince-edward-visits-tennessee-to-promote-duke-of-edinburgh-s/article_7a2225c9-8d6a-5038-a435-055c068e955e.html|title=Prince Edward visits Tennessee to promote Duke of Edinburgh's Award|publisher=The Daily Times|first=Erik|last=Schelzig|date=23 May 2013|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.hackney.gov.uk/the-duke-of-edinburghs-award-diamond-anniversary-royally-celebrated-in-hackney/|title=The Duke of Edinburgh's Award Diamond Anniversary royally celebrated in Hackney|publisher=Hackney Council|date=11 November 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In addition to being the chair of the Duke of Edinburgh's International Award Foundation, Edward is also a trustee of the International Award Association, which \"encompasses the DofE UK and all its other 61 National Award Authorities across the globe\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brightfuturetrust.org.uk/the-duke-of-edinburgh-award-international-association/|title=The Duke of Edinburgh Award International Association|publisher=Bright Future Trust|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> He was also chair of its international council and in 1999 founded the International Special Projects Group \"to provide a capital fund to broaden the reach of the Award\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jis.gov.jm/government/visits/earl-countess-wessex-visit-jamaica/|title=The Earl and Countess of Wessex to Visit Jamaica [March 2014]|publisher=Jamaica Information Service|year=2014|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:The Earl of Wessex in 2011 cropped.jpg|thumb|The Earl of Wessex at [[Yate]], Gloucestershire, December 2011]]\nIn June 2011, Edward visited [[Baltimore]] to meet the students and staff of the Living Classrooms Foundation and encourage them to participate in the Duke of Edinburgh's Award's programme.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.baltimoresun.com/bs-md-ci-prince-edward-visit-20110621-story.html|title=Prince Edward presents city's youth a royal challenge|newspaper=The Baltimore Sun|first=Erica|last=Green|date=21 June 2011|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In December 2011, the Earl and Countess of Wessex visited troops in Afghanistan. On the same trip, the royal couple visited [[Bahrain]], and received two gifts of jewels from the Bahraini royal family and Prime Minister. Given concern about human rights abuses in Bahrain, this gift attracted controversy, with calls for the jewels to be sold, and the proceeds used for the benefit of the [[Economy of Bahrain|Bahraini people]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/8999872/How-a-routine-royal-visit-spelt-trouble-for-the-Countess-of-Wessex.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Patrick | last=Sawer | title=How a routine royal visit spelt trouble for the Countess of Wessex | date=8 January 2012}}</ref> In February and March 2012, the couple visited the Caribbean for the Diamond Jubilee. The itinerary consisted of [[Saint Lucia]]; [[Barbados]], [[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines]]; [[Grenada]]; [[Trinidad and Tobago]]; [[Montserrat]]; [[Saint Kitts and Nevis]]; [[Anguilla]]; [[Antigua and Barbuda]]. Highlights included Independence Day celebrations in Saint Lucia,<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.thedominican.net/2012/02/royals-to-begin-visit.html | title=Royals to begin Caribbean tour bypasses Dominica|date= 16 February 2012|newspaper= The Dominican|accessdate= 19 February 2012}}</ref> addressing [[Parliament of Barbados|Senate and Assembly of Barbados]] jointly,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/ |first= Sharon |last= Lynch |title= Barbados: Royal Visit To Mark Queen's Diamond Jubilee |date= 27 January 2012 |newspaper= Bajan Sun Online |accessdate= 6 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://archive.is/20120719162855/http://www.bajansunonline.com/barbados-royal-visit-to-mark-queens-diamond-jubilee/ |archivedate= 19 July 2012 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> and a visit to sites affected by the volcanic eruptions in Montserrat.\n\nIn 2013, the couple visited South Africa.<ref name=\"Tel-2013\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/10469258/Sophie-Wessex-The-unsung-star-of-the-Royal-family.html|title=Sophie Wessex: The unsung star of the Royal family|newspaper=The Telegraph|first=Ingrid|last=Seward|date=23 November 2013}}</ref> The Queen appointed the Earl of Wessex as [[Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland]] for 2014.<ref name=\"Government\">{{Citation | year =2014 | title = The Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland | publisher = Government | url = https://www.gov.uk/government/news/the-lord-high-commissioner-to-the-general-assembly-of-the-church-of-scotland-2014}}.</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Edinburgh Gazette |issue=27354 |date=17 January 2014 |page=65 |city=e }}</ref> In 2015, for his contributions to projects associated with badminton, Edward was awarded the President's Medal by the [[Badminton World Federation]] President [[Poul-Erik Hoyer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.badmintonscotland.org.uk/news/2015/november/badmintonscotland-patron-hrh-the-earl-of-wessex-honoured-with-bwf-presidents-medal/|title=BADMINTONscotland Patron, HRH The Earl of Wessex honoured with BWF President's Medal|publisher=Badminton Scotland|date=November 2015|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In May 2016, the Earl visited Ghana. Alongside President Mahama, he presented young people with the Head of State Awards for their participation in the Duke of Edinburgh's International Award Scheme.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/prince-edward-to-visit-ghana-2|title=Prince Edward to visit Ghana|publisher=Gov.uk|date=20 May 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> In September 2016, Edward travelled to Chile as a part of the Duke of Edinburgh's Award's diamond anniversary, and visited projects by British and Commonwealth Fire and Rescue Company and Chilean-British Culture University, of which he is an honorary member and patron respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/youth-community-and-service-visit-by-hrh-prince-edward-to-chile|title=Youth, Community and Service; Visit by HRH Prince Edward to Chile|publisher=Gov.uk|date=22 September 2016|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref> The Earl and Countess of Wessex represented the Queen at the [[50th Anniversary Celebrations of Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah's Accession to the Throne of Brunei]] in October 2017.<ref name=\"thecrownchronicles.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecrownchronicles.co.uk/royal-news/edward-sophie-attend-sultan-bruneis-golden-jubilee-celebrations/|title=Edward & Sophie attend Sultan of Brunei's Golden Jubilee celebrations|publisher=thecrownchronicles.co.uk|accessdate=10 May 2018}}</ref> In February 2018, the Earl and Countess toured [[Sri Lanka]], participating in the 70th Independence Day celebrations in Colombo.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/earl-and-countess-wessex-commemorate-sri-lankas-70th-anniversary-independence|title=The Earl and Countess of Wessex commemorate Sri Lanka's 70th Anniversary of Independence|publisher=royal.uk|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ft.lk/news/Foreign-invitees-to-Independence-Day-Anniversary-celebrations-call-on-President/56-648838 Foreign invitees to Independence Day Anniversary celebrations call on President]</ref> In April 2018, the Earl visited Australia to attend the [[2018 Commonwealth Games|XXI Commonwealth Games]] and attend fundraising events for those participating in the Duke of Edinburgh Award challenges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themercury.com.au/news/tasmania/prince-edward-in-town-to-promote-duke-of-edinburghs-international-awards/news-story/d69d1e60ba09909e9e3e305ef1fc5896|title=Prince Edward in town to promote Duke of Edinburgh's International Awards|publisher=The Mercury|date=2 April 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/nation/prince-edward-arrives-in-melbourne-for-duke-of-edinburgh-international-awards-ceremony/news-story/74a8ec19c7c6b54b0b2999567a3c03cb|title=Prince Edward arrives in Melbourne for Duke of Edinburgh International Awards ceremony|publisher=The Weekend Australian|first=Samantha|last=Hutchinson|date=6 April 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter twenty years, the Wessex Youth Trust is reverting to its previous name \u2013 The Earl and Countess of Wessex Charitable Trust \u2013 and will be managed by the Private Office of the Earl and Countess of Wessex. There will be no change to the Trust's broad charitable objectives: it will focus on developing sustainable relationships with a range of selected partner charities and will expand its remit beyond supporting children and young people.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wessexyouthtrust.org.uk/index.php|title=Changes to The Wessex Youth Trust|publisher=wessexyouthtrust.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the Earl and Countess visited [[Forfar]] on their first official visit to the town since the Queen granted the Earl the additional title [[Earl of Forfar]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/earl-and-countess-forfar-visit-forfar|title=The Earl and Countess of Forfar visit Forfar|publisher=royal.uk|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> The Earl was presented with 'Earl of Forfar' [[tartan]], which has been designed to celebrate their new titles by town firm the Strathmore Woollen Company. The weave is based on the existing Forfar tartan, which the company designed in 2004 around the colours on the Forfar coat of arms. The geometry remains virtually the same, but the colours have been strengthened, with [[Azure blue]] replaced by the St Andrew's blue of the [[Scottish flag]], and white yarns replaced by a brown to reflect the rich agriculture of the surrounding area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/local/angus-mearns/926177/video-honour-to-be-named-earl-of-forfar-says-prince-edward-as-town-welcomes-him-with-bridies-tartan-and-fiddles/|title=VIDEO: 'Honour' to be named Earl of Forfar says Prince Edward as town welcomes him with bridies, tartan and fiddles|publisher=thecourier.co.uk|accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=RoyalFamily|author=The Royal Family|number=1145699686654853131|date=1 July 2019|title=His Royal Highness is presented with 'Earl of Forfar' tartan, which has been designed for Their Royal Highnesses to celebrate their new titles.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tartanregister.gov.uk/tartanDetails?ref=12595|title=Tartan Details - Earl of Forfar, The|publisher=tartanregister.gov.uk|accessdate=31 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n\n===Titles and styles===\n* 10 March 1964 \u2013 19 June 1999: ''His Royal Highness'' The Prince Edward\n* 19 June 1999 \u2013 present: ''His Royal Highness'' The Earl of Wessex<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55536 |date=28 June 1999 |page=7011 }}</ref>\n**in Scotland: 10 March 2019 \u2013 present: ''His Royal Highness'' The Earl of Forfar<ref name=forfar>{{Cite web | url = https://www.royal.uk/title-earl-wessex| title = Title for the Earl of Wessex | publisher = The Royal Family }}</ref><ref name=\"gazette2019\">{{London Gazette |issue=62588 |date=15 March 2019 | page=4737 |endpage= |supp=}}</ref>\nBefore Edward's marriage in 1999, royal commentators conjectured that former royal dukedoms such as [[Duke of Cambridge|Cambridge]] or [[Duke of Sussex|Sussex]] might be granted to him. Instead, the [[Buckingham Palace|Palace]] announced the intention that Prince Edward would eventually be created [[Duke of Edinburgh]], once that title had reverted to The Crown upon the death of both his parents.<ref>{{Cite web | url = http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/Stylesandtitles.aspx | title = The Earl of Wessex - Styles and titles | publisher = The Royal Family | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904051612/http://www.royal.gov.uk/ThecurrentRoyalFamily/TheEarlofWessex/Stylesandtitles.aspx |archivedate=4 September 2014}}.</ref>{{efn|The Earl of Wessex would not automatically succeed his father, as titles are passed to the eldest son; hence, the current Prince of Wales would succeed the present Duke. Once the Prince of Wales succeeds to the throne, any titles he has inherited (or will later inherit, if the current Duke is still alive) from his father will merge with the Crown, and he will be free to re-create the Dukedom of Edinburgh}}\n\nOn his marriage in 1999, the prince was ennobled in keeping with tradition, however he was the first prince since the Tudors to be known as an earl rather than a duke (while reserving the rank of duke for the future).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.debretts.com/people/essential-guide-peerage/ranks-and-privileges-peerage/duke|title=Duke|publisher=[[Debrett's]]|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref> ''[[The Sunday Telegraph]]'' reported that he was drawn to the Earldom of Wessex after watching the 1998 film ''[[Shakespeare in Love]]'', in which a character with that title is played by [[Colin Firth]].<ref name= \"EdwardSundayTelegraph\">{{cite web |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/royal-wedding/8196402/Royal-wedding-Prince-William-asks-the-Queen-not-to-make-him-a-duke.html |title=Royal wedding: Prince William asks the Queen not to make him a duke| first =Richard | last = Eden|date= 12 December 2010 |work= The Telegraph|accessdate= 12 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2019, on his 55th birthday, the Earl of Wessex was granted the additional title of [[Earl of Forfar]] for use in Scotland.<ref name=forfar/><ref name=\"gazette2019\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.msn.com/en-ca/lifestyle/lifestyleroyals/the-queen-gives-prince-edward-an-incredible-gift-on-his-birthday/ar-BBUC7fH?ocid=spartandhp |title=The Queen gives Prince Edward an incredible gift on his birthday |first=Hollie |last=Richardson |work=[[Hello! (magazine)|Hello!]] |publisher=[[MSN|msn Lifestyle]] |date=10 March 2019 |access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Honours===\n{{see also|List of honours of the British royal family by country}}\n\n* [[File:QEII Silver Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 1977: [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2002: [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[Image:Order of the Garter UK ribbon.png|45px]] 23 April 2006: [[Order of the Garter|Royal Knight of the Most Noble Order of the Garter]] (KG)<ref name=\"BuckPress\">{{Cite press release |title=Appointments to the Order of the Garter 2006 |date=23 April 2006 |publisher=Official website of the Royal Family |url=https://www.royal.uk/appointments-order-garter-2006 |quote=The Queen has also been graciously pleased to appoint His Royal Highness The Earl of Wessex, KCVO, to be a Royal Knight Companion of the Most Noble Order of the Garter.}}</ref>\n* [[File:Royal Victorian Order UK ribbon.png|45px]] 10 March 2011: [[Knight Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]] (GCVO)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59724 |date=11 March 2011 |page=4555 |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n** 2 June 2003{{spaced ndash}} 10 March 2011: Knight Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (KCVO)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56951 |date=2 June 2003 |page=6753 |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n** 10 March 1989{{spaced ndash}} 2 June 2003: Commander of the Royal Victorian Order (CVO)<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=51673 |date=14 March 1989 |page=3193 |nolink=yes }}</ref>\n* [[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2012: [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]\n\n====Commonwealth====\n* [[File:New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 9 February 1990: [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal|New Zealand Commemorative Medal]]\n* [[File:Saskatchewan Order of Merit ribbon bar 2005.svg|45px]] 11 May 2005: [[Saskatchewan Order of Merit|Honorary Member of the Saskatchewan Order of Merit]] (SOM)<ref name=sask>{{cite press release| title=Prince Edward Awarded Saskatchewan Order of Merit| publisher=Government of Saskatchewan| date=11 May 2005| url=http://www.gov.sk.ca/news?newsId=ca1c6377-29fe-4180-8fc9-3e58b0313f1f| accessdate=27 October 2008| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007012817/http://www.gov.sk.ca/news?newsId=ca1c6377-29fe-4180-8fc9-3e58b0313f1f| archivedate=7 October 2008| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[File:SCM ribbon.png|45px]] 7 June 2005: [[Commemorative Medal for the Centennial of Saskatchewan]]\n* [[File:CD-ribbon.png|45px]] 29 October 2015: [[Canadian Forces Decoration|Canadian Forces' Decoration]]<ref>{{Citation |title=Honours & recognition for the men and women of the Canadian Forces 2015 |url=http://publications.gc.ca/collections/collection_2016/mdn-dnd/D3-23-2015-eng.pdf |work=Department of National Defence |page=28}}</ref>\n* [[File:Sultan's Golden Jubilee Medal (2017).jpg|45px]] 5 October 2017: Sultan of Brunei Golden Jubilee Medal<ref>{{cite tweet|user=RoyalFamily|author=The Royal Family|number=915958265103732736|date=5 October 2017|title=The Earl and Countess of Wessex are in Brunei to attend The Sultan of Brunei's Golden Jubilee celebrations.}}</ref><ref name=\"thecrownchronicles.co.uk\"/>\n\n====Military appointments====\n* October 1986{{spaced ndash}}January 1987: [[Officer Cadet]], [[Royal Marines]]\n* 1 August 2004{{spaced ndash}}present: [[Personal Aide-de-Camp|Personal Aide-de-Camp to Her Majesty The Queen]] (AdC(P))\n\n=====Honorary military appointments=====\n;{{Flagicon|CAN}} Canada\n* 2002: [[Colonel-in-Chief]] of [[the Hastings and Prince Edward Regiment]]\n* 2003: Colonel-in-Chief of the [[Saskatchewan Dragoons]]\n* 2005: Colonel-in-Chief of [[the Prince Edward Island Regiment]]\n* 2007: Honorary Deputy Commissioner of the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]]\n\n;{{Flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n[[File:Prince Edward 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Prince Edward wearing the barrack dress uniform of in [[The Rifles]] in the rank of [[colonel]] (2014)]]\n* 2003: Royal [[Honorary Colonel]] of the [[Royal Wessex Yeomanry]]