{"title_page": "The Rio Times", "text_new": "{{Notability|Products|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Rio Times\n| image = The Rio Times Print Version November 2011.jpg\n| image_size = 240px\n| caption = The November 2011 front page of ''The Rio Times''\n| alt = \n| type = Online news and features services, and monthly printed newspaper\n| price = \n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| foundation = March 2009 ({{age in years and months|2009|3|1}})\n| headquarters = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| editor = Matthias Camenzind\n| website = [http://www.riotimesonline.com/ www.riotimesonline.com]\n}}\n'''''The Rio Times''''' is an [[English Language|English]]-language local [[newspaper]] and news and features [[website]] based in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].\n\n==Mission and Coverage==\nThe Rio Times is an English language publication dedicated to anyone interested in Brazil and Latin America. Beyond keeping up with national and local events, The Rio Times also covers issues of specific interest to foreign nationals in Brazil. The paper\u2019s mission is to provide our readers with a broad spectrum of information and improve their understanding of Rio de Janeiro, S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil, and Latin America.\n\n\nIn 2019 The Rio Times started to invest significantly more in reporting from all over Latin America. A third of all daily contributions today report on Latin America while two thirds deal with Brazil.\n\n==Online Newspaper==\n\nThe Rio Times produced its first printed version, which was increased from 5,000 to 10,000 in December 2011. It is distributed to a range of hotels and places popular with the [[English-speaking|Anglophone]] [[expatriate|expat]] community.                        \n\nThe print version was abandoned in 2017. Since then The Rio Times has been published exclusively online 24/7.\n\n\nIn January 2020, The Rio Times recorded monthly single page views of 1.7 million.\n\nThe Rio Times is read in over 50 countries. Most readers come from the following countries:                        \n\nBrazil                       \n\nUnited Kingdom\n\nCanada                    \n\nIndia                        \n\nArgentina\n\nGermany                  \n\nAustralia                    \n\nNorway                    \n\n\n\nThe newspapers readership has the following age group distribution: \n\n55 - 64 (22.6%)\n\n65+      (19.3%\n\n25-34   (18.1%)\n\n45-54    (17.8%)\n\n35-44    (15.7%)\n\n\n==Editor==\nThe paper's publisher is Swiss-born Matthias Camenzind. who bought the The Rio times in March 2019 from its American founder Stone Korshak.\n\n\n==References==\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2016}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://twitter.com/TheRioTimes The Rio Times's page on [[Twitter]]]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/RioTimes The Rio Times's [[Facebook]] page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rio Times}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Brazil]]\n[[Category:English-language newspapers published in South America]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Media in Rio de Janeiro (city)]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Brazil]]\n\n\n{{brazil-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Notability|Products|date=December 2011}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = The Rio Times\n| image = The Rio Times Print Version November 2011.jpg\n| image_size = 240px\n| caption = The November 2011 front page of ''The Rio Times''\n| alt = \n| type = Online news and features services, and monthly printed newspaper\n| price = \n| language = [[English language|English]]\n| foundation = March 2009 ({{age in years and months|2009|3|1}})\n| headquarters = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| editor = Matthias Camenzind\n| website = [http://www.riotimesonline.com/ www.riotimesonline.com]\n}}\n'''''The Rio Times''''' is an [[English Language|English]]-language local [[newspaper]] and news and features [[website]] based in [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]].\n\n==Mission and Coverage==\nThe Rio Times is an English language publication dedicated to anyone interested in Brazil and Latin America. Beyond keeping up with national and local events, The Rio Times also covers issues of specific interest to foreign nationals in Brazil. The paper\u2019s mission is to provide our readers with a broad spectrum of information and improve their understanding of Rio de Janeiro, S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil, and Latin America.\n\n\nIn 2019 The Rio Times started to invest significantly more in reporting from all over Latin America. A third of all daily contributions today report on Latin America while two thirds deal with Brazil.\n\n==Online Newspaper==\n\nThe Rio Times produced its first printed version, which was increased from 5,000 to 10,000 in December 2011. It is distributed to a range of hotels and places popular with the [[English-speaking|Anglophone]] [[expatriate|expat]] community.                        \n\nThe print version was abandoned in 2017. Since then The Rio Times has been published exclusively online 24/7.\n\n\nIn January 2020, The Rio Times recorded monthly single page views of 1.7 million.\n\nThe Rio Times is read in over 50 countries. Most readers come from the following countries:day report on Latin America, while two-thirds report on Brazil.                        \n\nUSA                        \n\nBrazil                       \n\nUnited Kingdom\n\nCanada                    \n\nIndia                        \n\nArgentina\n\nGermany                  \n\nAustralia                    \n\nNorway                    \n\n\nThe newspaper readership has the following age group distribution: \n\n55 - 64 (22.6%)\n\n65+      (19.3%\n\n25-34   (18.1%)\n\n45-54    (17.8%)\n\n35-44    (15.7%)\n\n\n==Editor==\nThe paper's publisher is Swiss-born Matthias Camenzind. who bought the The Rio times in March 2019 from its American founder Stone Korshak.\n\n\n==References==\n{{unreferenced|date=October 2016}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* [https://twitter.com/TheRioTimes The Rio Times's page on [[Twitter]]]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/RioTimes The Rio Times's [[Facebook]] page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rio Times}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Brazil]]\n[[Category:English-language newspapers published in South America]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Media in Rio de Janeiro (city)]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Brazil]]\n\n\n{{brazil-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wotan Norcross", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Rio_Times"}
{"title_page": "DF-15", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|is_missile=yes\n|name = Dong Feng 15\n|image = File:Dongfeng-15B.JPG\n|type = [[SRBM]]\n|vehicle_range = {{convert|600|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15)<br/> {{convert|900|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15A)<br/> {{convert|800|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15B)<br/> {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15C)\n|filling = Nuclear 50-350kt, or conventional. [[Maneuverable reentry vehicle]]s <ref name=\"softwar\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.softwar.net/df15.html |title=NEW DONG FENG 15 |access-date=5 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206134626/http://www.softwar.net/df15.html |archive-date=6 February 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|yield = 90&nbsp;kt\n|engine = Single-stage solid-propellant rocket\n|guidance = [[Astro-inertial guidance]] (including [[ring-laser gyroscope]]) + [[Beidou Navigation Satellite System|Beidou]]\n|speed =\n|length = 9.1&nbsp;m\n|diameter = 1.0&nbsp;m\n|weight = 6,200&nbsp;kg\n|payload_capacity = 600&nbsp;kg\n|manufacturer = Academy of Rocket Motors Technology\n|unit_cost =\n|service = 1990\u2013present \n|used_by = [[People's Republic of China|PRC]]\n|accuracy = 10&nbsp;m<ref name=\"softwar\" /><ref name=\"missilethreat.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913003144/http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |archive-date=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|launch_platform=Road-mobile [[Transporter erector launcher|TEL]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Dong-Feng 15''' (a.k.a. DF-15, M-9, CSS-6) is a short-range ballistic missile developed by the [[People's Republic of China]]. The DF-15 and the newer [[DF-16]] are thought to be the only non-nuclear missiles in use by the [[People's Liberation Army]] [[Second Artillery Corps]]. The U.S. Department of Defense estimated in 2008 that China had 315\u2013355 DF-15 missiles and 90\u2013110 launchers.<ref>{{Cite document | title= Military Power of the People's Republic of China 2008 |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/China_Military_Report_08.pdf | publisher=Office of the Secretary of Defense |page=56 (p66 of PDF) | postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDevelopment on the DF-15 began in 1985 with a finalized design proposal being approved by the PLA in 1987.  From the late 1980s to the mid-1990s, testing of the missile was done in the [[Gobi Desert]].  The first public display of the missile took place at the Beijing Defense Exposition in 1986.  The SAC had allegedly deployed a small number of the missiles the following year.\n\nIn 1989, [[Libya]] has agreed to finance [[Syria]]'s purchase of M-9 missiles from China. sale missiles to Syria were cancelled under U.S. pressure in 1991.<ref>2004. REPORT TO CONGRESS of the. U.S.-CHINA ECONOMIC AND. SECURITY REVIEW COMMISSION. p.145</ref><ref>\u201cFuture of United States-China Policy\u201d. May 20, 1993. Washington, D.C. p.162</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe DF-15 uses a solid fuel, single-stage rocket. It is vertically launched from an eight-wheeled [[transporter erector launcher]] (TEL). The missile's trajectory is guided using small thrusters and an inertial guidance system on the warhead. The warhead is only a tenth of the size of the missile body. After the body and warhead separate, the body trails behind to camouflage the warhead. The [[terminal velocity]] of the missile is over Mach 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/world/china/df-15.htm |title=DF-15 (CSS-6 / M-9) \u2013 China Nuclear Forces |date=2005-05-06 |work=GlobalSecurity.org}}</ref> It can deliver a {{convert|500-750|kg|lb|abbr=on}} payload up to {{convert|600|km|mi}}, with accuracy of 300&nbsp;m [[circular error probability]] (CEP).<ref name=\"missilethreat.com\"/>\n\nThe DF-15A is a variant that employs control fins at the rear of the missile and on the reentry vehicle, [[GPS]] updates, and terminal radar guidance. Its payload is believed to be {{convert|600|kg|lb|abbr=on}} with a range of {{convert|900|km|mi|abbr=on}} and improved accuracy of 30\u201345&nbsp;m CEP. The DF-15B is a further upgraded variant with similar features, as well as an [[active radar seeker]] and [[laser rangefinder]]. It is capable of ranges between {{convert|50-800|km|mi|abbr=on}} with greater accuracy of 5\u201310&nbsp;m CEP.<ref name=\"missilethreat.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913003144/http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |archive-date=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe DF-15C is a [[bunker buster]] variant equipped with a deep-penetration warhead, with a range of {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} and accuracy of 15\u201320&nbsp;m CEP.  It was originally designed with the intention of destroying the [[Heng Shan Military Command Center]] in Taiwan's capital of [[Taipei]], which was built to withstand a 20 kiloton nuclear blast, a 2 kiloton conventional bomb blast, or an [[electromagnetic pulse]]; another target would be [[Chiashan Air Force Base]].  In the event of an invasion, the destruction of Taiwan's major command center would make it difficult to coordinate defenses.  The missile's range also threatens locations as far as [[Kyushu]] in Japan, U.S. military bases in Okinawa and the Indian capital of [[New Delhi]].<ref>[http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1101&MainCatID=&id=20140603000013 Photos published of China's DF-15C bunker buster] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714184601/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1101&MainCatID=&id=20140603000013 |date=14 July 2014 }} \u2013 Wantchinatimes.com, 3 June 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.news.com.au/technology/china-releases-first-photos-of-df15c-bunker-buster-shortrange-ballistic-missile-with-deeppenetration-warhead/story-e6frfrnr-1226942286149 China releases first photos of DF-15C \u2018bunker buster\u2019, short-range ballistic missile with deep-penetration warhead] \u2013 News.com.au, 4 June 2014</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[DF-16]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://missilethreat.csis.org/missile/df-15-css-6/ CSIS Missile Threat \u2013 DF-15]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060717000610/http://www.sinodefence.com/strategic/missile/df15.asp Sinodefense description]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=DF-15 |before=? |after=[[DF-16]] |years=1990\u2013present}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chinese_Missiles}}\n\n[[Category:Ballistic missiles of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Weapons of the People's Republic of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|is_missile=yes\n|name = Dong Feng 15\n|image = File:Dongfeng-15B.JPG\n|type = [[SRBM]]\n|vehicle_range = {{convert|600|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15)<br/> {{convert|900|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15A)<br/> {{convert|800|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15B)<br/> {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} (DF-15C)\n|filling = Nuclear 50-350kt, or conventional. [[Maneuverable reentry vehicle]]s <ref name=\"softwar\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.softwar.net/df15.html |title=NEW DONG FENG 15 |access-date=5 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206134626/http://www.softwar.net/df15.html |archive-date=6 February 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|yield = 90&nbsp;kt\n|engine = Single-stage solid-propellant rocket\n|guidance = [[Astro-inertial guidance]] (including [[ring-laser gyroscope]]) + [[Beidou Navigation Satellite System|Beidou]]\n|speed =\n|length = 9.1&nbsp;m\n|diameter = 1.0&nbsp;m\n|weight = 6,200&nbsp;kg\n|payload_capacity = 600&nbsp;kg\n|manufacturer = Academy of Rocket Motors Technology\n|unit_cost =\n|service = 1990-present \n|used_by = [[People's Republic of China|PRC]]\n|accuracy = 10&nbsp;m<ref name=\"softwar\" /><ref name=\"missilethreat.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913003144/http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |archive-date=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|launch_platform=Road-mobile [[Transporter erector launcher|TEL]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Dong-Feng 15''' (a.k.a. DF-15, M-9, CSS-6) is a short-range ballistic missile developed by the [[People's Republic of China]]. The DF-15 and the newer [[DF-16]] are thought to be the only non-nuclear missiles in use by the [[People's Liberation Army]] [[Second Artillery Corps]]. The U.S. Department of Defense estimated in 2008 that China had 315-355 DF-15 missiles and 90-110 launchers.<ref>{{Cite document | title= Military Power of the People's Republic of China 2008 |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/pubs/pdfs/China_Military_Report_08.pdf | publisher=Office of the Secretary of Defense |page=56 (p66 of PDF) | postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nDevelopment on the DF-15 began in 1985 with a finalized design proposal being approved by the PLA in 1987.  From the late 1980s to the mid-1990s, testing of the missile was done in the [[Gobi Desert]].  The first public display of the missile took place at the Beijing Defense Exposition in 1986.  The SAC had allegedly deployed a small number of the missiles the following year.\n\nIn 1989, [[Libya]] has agreed to finance [[Syria]]'s purchase of M-9 missiles from China. sale missiles to Syria were cancelled under U.S. pressure in 1991.<ref>2004. REPORT TO CONGRESS of the. U.S.-CHINA ECONOMIC AND. SECURITY REVIEW COMMISSION. p.145</ref><ref>\u201cFuture of United States-China Policy\u201d. May 20, 1993. Washington, D.C. p.162</ref>\n\n== Description ==\nThe DF-15 uses a solid fuel, single-stage rocket. It is vertically launched from an eight-wheeled [[transporter erector launcher]] (TEL). The missile's trajectory is guided using small thrusters and an inertial guidance system on the warhead. The warhead is only a tenth of the size of the missile body. After the body and warhead separate, the body trails behind to camouflage the warhead. The [[terminal velocity]] of the missile is over Mach 6.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/world/china/df-15.htm |title=DF-15 (CSS-6 / M-9) - China Nuclear Forces |date=2005-05-06 |work=GlobalSecurity.org}}</ref> It can deliver a {{convert|500-750|kg|lb|abbr=on}} payload up to {{convert|600|km|mi}}, with accuracy of 300&nbsp;m [[circular error probability]] (CEP).<ref name=\"missilethreat.com\"/>\n\nThe DF-15A is a variant that employs control fins at the rear of the missile and on the reentry vehicle, [[GPS]] updates, and terminal radar guidance. Its payload is believed to be {{convert|600|kg|lb|abbr=on}} with a range of {{convert|900|km|mi|abbr=on}} and improved accuracy of 30\u201345&nbsp;m CEP. The DF-15B is a further upgraded variant with similar features, as well as an [[active radar seeker]] and [[laser rangefinder]]. It is capable of ranges between {{convert|50-800|km|mi|abbr=on}} with greater accuracy of 5\u201310&nbsp;m CEP.<ref name=\"missilethreat.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913003144/http://missilethreat.com/missiles/df-15-15a-15b-css-6m-9/ |archive-date=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe DF-15C is a [[bunker buster]] variant equipped with a deep-penetration warhead, with a range of {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}} and accuracy of 15\u201320&nbsp;m CEP.  It was originally designed with the intention of destroying the [[Heng Shan Military Command Center]] in Taiwan's capital of [[Taipei]], which was built to withstand a 20 kiloton nuclear blast, a 2 kiloton conventional bomb blast, or an [[electromagnetic pulse]]; another target would be [[Chiashan Air Force Base]].  In the event of an invasion, the destruction of Taiwan's major command center would make it difficult to coordinate defenses.  The missile's range also threatens locations as far as [[Kyushu]] in Japan, U.S. military bases in Okinawa and the Indian capital of [[New Delhi]].<ref>[http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1101&MainCatID=&id=20140603000013 Photos published of China's DF-15C bunker buster] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714184601/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?cid=1101&MainCatID=&id=20140603000013 |date=14 July 2014 }} - Wantchinatimes.com, 3 June 2014</ref><ref>[http://www.news.com.au/technology/china-releases-first-photos-of-df15c-bunker-buster-shortrange-ballistic-missile-with-deeppenetration-warhead/story-e6frfrnr-1226942286149 China releases first photos of DF-15C \u2018bunker buster\u2019, short-range ballistic missile with deep-penetration warhead] - News.com.au, 4 June 2014</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[DF-16]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://missilethreat.csis.org/missile/df-15-css-6/ CSIS Missile Threat - DF-15]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060717000610/http://www.sinodefence.com/strategic/missile/df15.asp Sinodefense description]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|title=DF-15 |before=? |after=[[DF-16]] |years=1990\u2013present}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chinese_Missiles}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Ballistic missiles of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Weapons of the People's Republic of China]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DF-15"}
